const CLF_QUESTIONS = [
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A startup wants to launch a web application globally without purchasing servers or paying upfront costs. Which cloud benefit enables this?","options":["Paying a fixed monthly fee for reserved capacity", "Signing a 3-year contract for discounted server rates", "Trade capital expense for variable operational expense with pay-as-you-go pricing", "Purchasing physical servers in each target region"],"answer":2,"explain":"Cloud computing transforms CapEx (buying servers upfront) into OpEx (paying for what you use). This eliminates upfront investment and lets startups scale spending with actual usage."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company's e-commerce site experiences 10x traffic during Black Friday. What cloud benefit allows them to handle this automatically?","options":["High availability through multiple data centers", "Elasticity — automatically scaling resources up and down based on demand", "Economies of scale from shared infrastructure", "Global reach through CDN distribution"],"answer":1,"explain":"Elasticity is the ability to automatically provision and de-provision resources to match demand. AWS Auto Scaling adds capacity during Black Friday peaks and removes it after, paying only for what was used."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which cloud deployment model keeps all infrastructure on-premises with no cloud connectivity?","options":["Private cloud — dedicated infrastructure operated solely for one organization", "Public cloud using shared AWS infrastructure", "Hybrid cloud combining on-premises and public cloud", "Community cloud shared among organizations with similar requirements"],"answer":0,"explain":"Private cloud deploys dedicated infrastructure exclusively for one organization, either on-premises or in a dedicated hosted facility. All resources are isolated from other organizations."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company uses both AWS for new workloads and keeps legacy apps on-premises. What deployment model is this?","options":["Pure public cloud using only AWS services", "Private cloud with on-premises resources only", "Hybrid cloud combining on-premises and AWS cloud resources", "Multi-cloud using multiple public cloud providers"],"answer":2,"explain":"Hybrid cloud integrates on-premises infrastructure with public cloud services. AWS Direct Connect and VPN provide secure connectivity between the data center and AWS, enabling workload portability."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"AWS operates data centers in multiple geographic locations worldwide. What is each distinct geographic location called?","options":["AWS Region — geographic area with multiple availability zones", "Availability Zone — isolated data center within a region", "Edge Location — CloudFront CDN point of presence", "Local Zone — AWS infrastructure extension near cities"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Regions are distinct geographic areas (us-east-1, eu-west-1, etc.) each containing multiple Availability Zones. Choosing the right region affects latency, compliance, and disaster recovery."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is an AWS Availability Zone?","options":["One or more discrete data centers with redundant power, networking, and connectivity within a Region", "A separate AWS Region in a different country", "An AWS edge location serving CloudFront content", "A virtual private cloud network segment"],"answer":0,"explain":"An Availability Zone (AZ) is one or more physically separate data centers within a Region, each with independent power, cooling, and networking. Deploying across multiple AZs provides high availability."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS concept describes the ability to acquire resources instantly and release them when no longer needed, with no human interaction?","options":["On-demand self-service — provision resources without human intervention", "Broad network access through internet connectivity", "Resource pooling sharing infrastructure among multiple customers", "Measured service tracking resource usage for billing"],"answer":0,"explain":"On-demand self-service is a fundamental cloud characteristic: users can provision compute, storage, and networking resources instantly through a console or API without requiring human assistance from the provider."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company benefits from AWS's massive scale which allows AWS to offer lower prices. What cloud benefit does this represent?","options":["Elasticity scaling resources with demand", "Increased speed and agility launching resources in minutes", "Massive economies of scale driving lower pay-as-you-go prices", "Global reach deploying in multiple regions"],"answer":2,"explain":"Because AWS serves hundreds of thousands of customers, it achieves economies of scale that result in lower variable costs, which AWS passes on through lower prices than any single company could achieve on its own."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A developer can launch a new server on AWS in minutes instead of the weeks required to procure physical hardware. What cloud advantage is this?","options":["Elasticity handling variable workloads efficiently", "Economies of scale reducing infrastructure costs", "Increased speed and agility — provision resources in minutes not months", "Stop guessing capacity by scaling based on actual demand"],"answer":2,"explain":"Cloud dramatically increases speed and agility: resources that took weeks to procure (purchase order, shipping, rack, configure) now take minutes via console or API, enabling rapid innovation and experimentation."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What does the AWS shared responsibility model define?","options":["How AWS and customers share cost savings from Reserved Instances", "The division of security responsibilities between AWS and the customer", "How multiple AWS customers share physical hardware resources", "The service level agreement between AWS and enterprise customers"],"answer":1,"explain":"The shared responsibility model divides security: AWS is responsible for security 'of' the cloud (hardware, software, networking, facilities). Customers are responsible for security 'in' the cloud (data, applications, identity, network config)."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Under the AWS shared responsibility model, which of the following is AWS responsible for?","options":["Encrypting customer data stored in S3", "Patching the hypervisor and physical host infrastructure", "Managing IAM users and their permissions", "Configuring security groups on EC2 instances"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS manages and patches the physical infrastructure, hypervisor, and managed service software. Customers manage their OS patches, application security, IAM, and network configuration."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS Support plan provides access to a Technical Account Manager (TAM) and is designed for enterprise customers with mission-critical workloads?","options":["Basic Support — free tier with documentation access", "Developer Support — business hours email support", "Business Support — 24/7 phone and chat support", "Enterprise Support — TAM plus proactive guidance"],"answer":3,"explain":"Enterprise Support includes a dedicated Technical Account Manager (TAM) who provides proactive guidance, architectural reviews, and helps customers plan, deploy, and optimize their AWS environments."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants to migrate its data center to AWS to eliminate the cost of managing physical hardware. What cloud benefit does this represent?","options":["Go global in minutes by deploying in multiple regions", "Increase speed and agility through rapid resource provisioning", "Stop spending money running and maintaining data centers", "Trade variable expense for capital expense"],"answer":2,"explain":"Eliminating data center operations (power, cooling, physical security, hardware refresh cycles) is a core cloud benefit. Companies redirect that capital and staff effort toward innovation rather than infrastructure maintenance."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the primary difference between IaaS, PaaS, and SaaS?","options":["They differ only in pricing model — hourly vs monthly vs annual", "The level of management responsibility: IaaS gives most control, SaaS gives least with the provider managing most", "IaaS is for storage, PaaS is for compute, SaaS is for networking", "They are identical services with different marketing names"],"answer":1,"explain":"IaaS (EC2) — you manage OS, runtime, apps. PaaS (Elastic Beanstalk) — provider manages OS/runtime, you manage apps. SaaS (Workmail) — provider manages everything, you just use the service."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS service provides a unified view of all AWS accounts and enables consolidated billing for an organization?","options":["AWS Organizations for multi-account management and consolidated billing", "AWS IAM for identity management across accounts", "AWS Control Tower for account governance automation", "AWS Config for compliance tracking across accounts"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Organizations groups multiple AWS accounts under a master payer account, enabling consolidated billing (single invoice, volume discounts), service control policies, and centralized account governance."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants to stop guessing how much infrastructure capacity they need. Which cloud benefit addresses this?","options":["Benefit from massive economies of scale reducing fixed costs", "Trade capital expense for variable expense with pay-as-you-go", "Stop guessing capacity — scale up or down as actual needs change", "Go global in minutes using multiple AWS regions"],"answer":2,"explain":"With AWS, you provision based on actual demand instead of peak estimates. If you over-provision, you pay for idle capacity. Under-provision and you can't handle load. AWS Auto Scaling eliminates this guessing game."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What are AWS edge locations primarily used for?","options":["Caching CloudFront content and running Route 53 DNS closer to users for lower latency", "Running EC2 instances closer to end users", "Hosting dedicated RDS databases near customers", "Providing Direct Connect colocation facilities"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS edge locations are CloudFront CDN points of presence that cache content close to end users, reducing latency. They also host Route 53 DNS resolvers and Lambda@Edge functions for edge computing."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which of the following is an example of a managed AWS service where AWS handles patching, scaling, and availability?","options":["EC2 instance where you install and manage your own database", "Amazon RDS — AWS manages database engine, backups, patching, and failover", "EC2 with a self-managed Kubernetes cluster", "An EC2-hosted application behind an Elastic Load Balancer"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon RDS is a managed database service — AWS handles database patching, automated backups, Multi-AZ failover, and scaling. You manage database configuration and data, not the underlying infrastructure."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What does 'high availability' mean in AWS architecture?","options":["A design that minimizes downtime by eliminating single points of failure across multiple AZs", "A system that never experiences any downtime or errors whatsoever", "Deploying applications in all AWS regions simultaneously", "Using the most powerful EC2 instance type for critical workloads"],"answer":0,"explain":"High availability minimizes downtime by distributing workloads across multiple Availability Zones, using load balancers, Auto Scaling, and managed services with built-in redundancy to survive individual component failures."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company needs to choose between deploying in a single large EC2 instance vs many smaller ones. What AWS design principle do multiple smaller instances support?","options":["Cost optimization through instance consolidation", "Performance efficiency using the most powerful instance types", "Design for failure — assume any component can fail and architect to survive it", "Operational excellence through simplified management"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Well-Architected Pillar: Reliability. Design for failure means assuming any single component will fail. Multiple smaller instances across AZs means no single failure takes down the application."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the AWS Well-Architected Framework?","options":["A set of AWS pricing guidelines for optimizing cloud costs", "A compliance standard for regulated industries using AWS", "AWS documentation for setting up initial account configurations", "A framework of best practices across five pillars for building secure, reliable, efficient, and cost-effective systems"],"answer":3,"explain":"The AWS Well-Architected Framework provides five pillars: Operational Excellence, Security, Reliability, Performance Efficiency, and Cost Optimization. Each pillar has design principles and best practices questions."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which pillar of the AWS Well-Architected Framework focuses on running and monitoring systems to deliver business value and continuously improve processes?","options":["Security — protecting information and systems", "Reliability — ensuring workload performs correctly consistently", "Operational Excellence — running and improving operations effectively", "Performance Efficiency — using resources efficiently"],"answer":2,"explain":"Operational Excellence covers automation of operations, responding to events, and continuously improving processes and procedures. It includes performing operations as code and making small, reversible changes."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants to evaluate their AWS architecture against best practices. Which free AWS tool provides this assessment?","options":["AWS Well-Architected Tool for structured architectural review", "AWS Trusted Advisor checking against best practices", "AWS Config evaluating resource configuration compliance", "AWS Inspector scanning for security vulnerabilities"],"answer":0,"explain":"The AWS Well-Architected Tool provides a consistent process to review architectures against the six pillars, identify high-risk issues, and generate improvement plans through a series of questions."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the concept of 'loose coupling' in cloud architecture?","options":["Using low-cost EC2 instances to reduce infrastructure spending", "Encrypting data loosely to balance security and performance", "Combining multiple services into a single tightly integrated application", "Designing components to minimize dependencies so failures don't cascade"],"answer":3,"explain":"Loose coupling reduces dependencies between components using queues (SQS), APIs, and event systems (EventBridge). If one component fails, others continue working independently, improving resilience."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What distinguishes a 'serverless' architecture from a traditional server-based one?","options":["Serverless uses no computing resources at all", "Serverless requires more configuration than traditional server management", "Serverless is only suitable for small applications under 100 users", "Serverless means you don't provision or manage servers — the cloud provider handles scaling and availability automatically"],"answer":3,"explain":"Serverless (Lambda, DynamoDB, S3) means you write code or use services without provisioning or managing servers. AWS handles scaling, patching, and availability automatically. You pay only per invocation/usage."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is a key characteristic of cloud computing related to how multiple customers use the same physical infrastructure?","options":["On-demand self-service with instant provisioning", "Rapid elasticity scaling resources up and down on demand", "Measured service billing based on actual consumption", "Resource pooling serving multiple customers from shared physical resources with multi-tenancy"],"answer":3,"explain":"Resource pooling is a core cloud characteristic where the provider serves multiple customers from a shared pool of physical resources, with customers getting virtual resources from a common infrastructure, achieving economies of scale."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS program helps customers migrate workloads to AWS by providing credits, training, and technical resources?","options":["AWS Free Tier for experimenting with AWS services", "AWS Marketplace for purchasing third-party software", "AWS Migration Acceleration Program (MAP) for enterprise migrations", "AWS Partner Network for technology partner solutions"],"answer":2,"explain":"The AWS Migration Acceleration Program (MAP) provides financial, operational, and technical support including migration credits, training, and AWS Solutions Architect engagement for large-scale enterprise migrations."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the difference between 'vertical scaling' and 'horizontal scaling' on AWS?","options":["Vertical scaling adds more instances; horizontal adds more capacity to one instance", "Vertical scaling increases the size/power of one instance; horizontal scaling adds more instances", "They are identical approaches with different AWS service names", "Vertical scaling is for databases; horizontal scaling is for web servers only"],"answer":1,"explain":"Vertical scaling (scale up) increases instance size (t3.medium → m5.large). Horizontal scaling (scale out) adds more instances behind a load balancer. Horizontal is preferred for cloud-native, fault-tolerant architectures."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants to test a new idea by spinning up resources for 2 hours, testing, then shutting down with minimal cost. What cloud benefit supports this?","options":["Ability to experiment quickly and cheaply — provision, test, then de-provision paying only for 2 hours", "Economies of scale reducing long-term infrastructure costs", "High availability ensuring continuous uptime during testing", "Global reach for deploying tests in multiple regions"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cloud enables cheap experimentation — try new ideas with minimal cost and risk. Failed experiments can be shut down immediately. This accelerates innovation cycles compared to waiting weeks and spending thousands on physical hardware."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is 'fault tolerance' and how does it differ from high availability?","options":["They are identical concepts meaning systems never experience outages", "Fault tolerance means zero downtime and zero data loss; high availability means minimal downtime with quick recovery", "Fault tolerance is for databases; high availability is for web applications", "High availability requires multiple regions; fault tolerance uses only one region"],"answer":1,"explain":"Fault tolerance (zero downtime, zero data loss) is stricter than high availability (minimal downtime). FT uses full redundancy with instant failover. HA accepts brief interruptions during failover. Both are achieved through multi-AZ deployment."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS service provides a global network of content delivery that caches content at edge locations near end users?","options":["Amazon Route 53 for global DNS routing", "Amazon CloudFront CDN for caching content at edge locations", "AWS Global Accelerator for network performance optimization", "Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration for fast uploads"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon CloudFront is a CDN with 400+ edge locations globally. It caches static and dynamic content near users, reducing latency and offloading origin servers. It integrates with S3, EC2, and custom origins."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the 'principle of least privilege' in AWS security?","options":["Using the smallest EC2 instances to minimize costs", "Granting users and services only the minimum permissions required for their specific tasks", "Reducing the number of AWS services used to simplify architecture", "Limiting AWS usage to the free tier to minimize spending"],"answer":1,"explain":"Least privilege is a security best practice: grant IAM users, roles, and services only the specific permissions they need for their job function. This minimizes the blast radius if credentials are compromised."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"AWS has data centers across the globe. What is the benefit of this global infrastructure for customers?","options":["All data is automatically replicated across all regions", "All AWS services are available in every region simultaneously", "Global infrastructure eliminates the need for disaster recovery planning", "Customers can deploy applications globally in minutes to reduce latency for users worldwide"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS's global infrastructure of 30+ regions enables companies to deploy applications close to users worldwide in minutes, reducing latency. Previously, global expansion required years of physical infrastructure setup."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to control which AWS services their developers can use across all accounts in their organization. Which service enforces this?","options":["IAM policies attached to individual user accounts", "AWS Organizations Service Control Policies (SCPs) restricting services at the organizational level", "AWS Config rules monitoring service usage compliance", "AWS CloudTrail logging all service API calls"],"answer":1,"explain":"Service Control Policies (SCPs) in AWS Organizations set maximum permission guardrails across all accounts in an OU or organization. Even account admins can't exceed SCP boundaries, enabling centralized governance."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service allows you to create and manage encryption keys used to protect your data, with full audit trails?","options":["AWS Key Management Service (KMS) for creating and managing cryptographic keys", "AWS Certificate Manager for SSL/TLS certificates", "AWS Secrets Manager for storing application credentials", "AWS CloudHSM for dedicated hardware security modules"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS KMS creates and manages Customer Master Keys (CMKs) for encrypting data across AWS services. It provides centralized key management, automatic rotation, and full CloudTrail audit logs of key usage."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to store database passwords and API keys securely with automatic rotation. Which AWS service is purpose-built for this?","options":["AWS KMS storing encryption keys", "AWS Secrets Manager for securely storing and rotating credentials", "AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store for configuration data", "Amazon S3 with server-side encryption for secret files"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Secrets Manager stores, manages, and automatically rotates secrets like database passwords, API keys, and OAuth tokens. It integrates with RDS, Redshift, and DocumentDB for native credential rotation."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is multi-factor authentication (MFA) and why is it critical for AWS root accounts?","options":["An additional authentication factor beyond password, critical for root accounts to prevent account takeover", "A backup authentication method used only when passwords expire", "A compliance requirement only for regulated industries", "An optional feature only needed for production accounts"],"answer":0,"explain":"MFA requires a second factor (TOTP app, hardware key) beyond the password. AWS root accounts have unrestricted access to all resources — if compromised, attackers can delete everything. MFA is mandatory best practice for root."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service monitors for malicious activity and unauthorized behavior across your AWS account using ML and threat intelligence?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty detecting threats using ML and threat intelligence", "AWS Config tracking configuration changes", "AWS Security Hub aggregating security findings", "Amazon Inspector scanning for vulnerabilities"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon GuardDuty analyzes CloudTrail logs, VPC Flow Logs, and DNS logs using ML and threat intelligence to detect threats like credential compromise, unusual API calls, and crypto mining without requiring agents."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to assess their EC2 instances for known vulnerabilities and unintended network exposure. Which service automates this?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty for threat detection", "Amazon Inspector for automated vulnerability assessment of EC2 and containers", "AWS Security Hub for compliance dashboard", "AWS Config for configuration compliance checking"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Inspector automatically scans EC2 instances and container images for software vulnerabilities (CVEs) and unintended network exposure, generating prioritized findings with remediation recommendations."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is AWS IAM and what does it control?","options":["A firewall service controlling inbound and outbound network traffic", "A monitoring service tracking user activity across AWS services", "Identity and Access Management — controls who can access which AWS resources and what they can do", "A VPN service providing secure network connectivity to AWS"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS IAM manages authentication (who can sign in) and authorization (what they can do) for AWS resources. It creates users, groups, roles, and policies that define permissions using the least privilege principle."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A developer accidentally commits AWS access keys to a public GitHub repository. What should be done immediately?","options":["Change the IAM user's password to prevent unauthorized access", "Contact GitHub to remove the committed keys from history", "Enable MFA on the account and wait 24 hours for the keys to expire", "Deactivate and delete the exposed access keys immediately, then create new ones"],"answer":3,"explain":"Exposed access keys must be immediately deactivated/deleted in IAM — they can be used within minutes of exposure. Check CloudTrail for unauthorized usage, then create new keys and update applications."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides a centralized security dashboard aggregating findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, and other security services?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty for threat detection aggregation", "Amazon CloudWatch for operational metrics and alarms", "AWS Security Hub for centralized security posture management", "AWS Config for compliance and configuration tracking"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Security Hub aggregates security findings from multiple AWS services and partner tools into a single dashboard, normalizes findings using ASFF format, and provides automated compliance checks (CIS, PCI, HIPAA)."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What does 'encryption at rest' protect against?","options":["Interception of data while it travels across networks", "Unauthorized access to stored data if physical storage media is stolen or accessed directly", "Unauthorized API calls made to AWS services", "Denial of service attacks on database resources"],"answer":1,"explain":"Encryption at rest protects stored data (S3 objects, EBS volumes, RDS databases) from unauthorized access if physical media is stolen or if someone bypasses access controls. AWS KMS manages the encryption keys."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service enables compliance with regulations by recording all API calls made within your AWS account?","options":["AWS CloudTrail logging all API calls for audit and compliance", "Amazon CloudWatch for performance monitoring and alerting", "AWS Config tracking resource configuration changes over time", "Amazon GuardDuty detecting suspicious API usage patterns"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS CloudTrail logs every API call made in your AWS account including who made it, what was done, and when. This audit trail is essential for security investigations, compliance audits, and detecting unauthorized actions."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company must comply with PCI DSS for credit card data. Which AWS program provides compliance reports and certifications?","options":["AWS Trusted Advisor checking security best practices", "AWS Security Hub running PCI DSS compliance checks", "AWS Artifact providing on-demand access to AWS compliance reports and certifications", "AWS Config rules for PCI DSS configuration compliance"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Artifact provides on-demand access to AWS security and compliance reports (SOC 2, PCI DSS, ISO 27001, HIPAA BAA) through a self-service portal, enabling customers to demonstrate AWS's compliance posture to auditors."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the purpose of AWS IAM roles vs IAM users?","options":["Roles are for humans; users are for applications and services", "Roles have more permissions than users by default", "Roles provide temporary credentials assumed by services/users without long-term access keys; users have permanent credentials", "Users can only access the console; roles can only access APIs"],"answer":2,"explain":"IAM roles provide temporary credentials via STS AssumeRole — perfect for EC2 instances, Lambda functions, and cross-account access. Unlike IAM users, roles have no long-term credentials to accidentally expose."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service protects web applications from common exploits like SQL injection and cross-site scripting (XSS)?","options":["AWS Shield protecting against DDoS attacks", "AWS WAF (Web Application Firewall) filtering malicious web traffic", "Amazon GuardDuty detecting web-based threats", "Amazon Inspector scanning web applications for vulnerabilities"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS WAF filters HTTP/HTTPS traffic using configurable rules, blocking common web attacks (OWASP Top 10 including SQL injection, XSS), bad bots, and rate-based rules. It integrates with CloudFront, ALB, and API Gateway."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to protect against large-scale DDoS attacks at the network and transport layers automatically. Which AWS service provides this for free?","options":["AWS WAF filtering application-layer attacks", "AWS Shield Standard protecting all AWS customers automatically at no charge", "Amazon GuardDuty detecting volumetric attack patterns", "AWS Firewall Manager managing WAF rules centrally"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Shield Standard is automatically included for all AWS customers at no cost. It provides always-on protection against common network layer (Layer 3/4) DDoS attacks on EC2, ELB, CloudFront, and Route 53."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is a Security Group in AWS?","options":["An IAM group with security-focused permissions attached", "A WAF rule group protecting web applications", "A network ACL filtering traffic at the subnet level", "A virtual firewall controlling inbound and outbound traffic for EC2 instances at the instance level"],"answer":3,"explain":"Security Groups are stateful virtual firewalls attached to EC2 instances (and other resources). They control traffic by port, protocol, and source/destination IP. Stateful means return traffic is automatically allowed."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"How does a Network ACL (NACL) differ from a Security Group?","options":["NACLs are stateless and operate at the subnet level; Security Groups are stateful at the instance level", "NACLs are for EC2; Security Groups are for VPCs", "Security Groups allow and deny; NACLs only allow traffic", "They are interchangeable and perform identical functions"],"answer":0,"explain":"NACLs operate at the subnet level and are stateless (must explicitly allow return traffic). Security Groups operate at the instance level and are stateful. Both provide layered defense for VPC resources."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to detect if sensitive data like credit card numbers is stored in their S3 buckets without their knowledge. Which service helps?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty monitoring S3 access patterns", "Amazon Inspector scanning S3 objects for vulnerabilities", "AWS Config checking S3 bucket configuration compliance", "Amazon Macie using ML to discover and protect sensitive data in S3"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon Macie uses ML to automatically discover, classify, and protect sensitive data (PII, financial data, credentials) in S3, providing visibility into what sensitive data you have and where it's stored."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS compliance program specifically addresses healthcare data protection requirements in the United States?","options":["HIPAA — AWS signs Business Associate Agreements for covered healthcare workloads", "PCI DSS for payment card industry compliance", "SOC 2 Type II for service organization controls", "ISO 27001 for information security management"],"answer":0,"explain":"HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) governs US healthcare data. AWS signs Business Associate Agreements (BAAs) and provides HIPAA-eligible services with appropriate safeguards for PHI."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the principle of 'defense in depth' in AWS security?","options":["Applying multiple overlapping layers of security controls so that if one fails others still protect", "Using only the most advanced security services for maximum protection", "Defending primarily at the network perimeter with minimal internal controls", "Using deep learning models to detect and respond to security threats"],"answer":0,"explain":"Defense in depth applies multiple security layers: network (VPC, NACLs), instance (Security Groups, patching), data (encryption), application (WAF), and identity (IAM, MFA). Multiple layers mean no single failure exposes data."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to centrally manage firewall rules across multiple AWS accounts and VPCs. Which service provides this?","options":["AWS WAF managing web application firewall rules per account", "Amazon Inspector centrally managing vulnerability scanning", "AWS Organizations SCPs restricting security service usage", "AWS Firewall Manager centrally managing security policies across accounts"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Firewall Manager centrally configures and manages WAF rules, AWS Shield Advanced, Security Groups, and Network Firewall policies across multiple accounts in AWS Organizations from a single place."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is AWS Cognito used for?","options":["Managing IAM users and their AWS console access", "Storing encrypted application secrets and passwords", "Adding user sign-up, sign-in, and access control to web and mobile applications", "Providing SSO access to AWS services for enterprise users"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon Cognito provides user authentication and authorization for applications — user pools for sign-up/sign-in, identity pools for granting AWS service access. It supports social logins (Google, Facebook) and SAML federation."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides single sign-on (SSO) access to multiple AWS accounts and business applications?","options":["AWS IAM for identity management across AWS accounts", "Amazon Cognito for customer-facing application authentication", "AWS IAM Identity Center (SSO) for unified access to AWS accounts and apps", "AWS Directory Service for Active Directory integration"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS IAM Identity Center (formerly AWS SSO) provides centralized SSO to multiple AWS accounts and SAML 2.0 applications (Salesforce, Office 365) using a unified portal, integrating with Active Directory."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company stores all infrastructure configuration in code (Terraform, CloudFormation). How does this support security?","options":["Infrastructure as Code reduces security risks by eliminating manual console access", "IaC eliminates the need for security testing of infrastructure", "IaC automatically encrypts all resources defined in the templates", "IaC enables consistent security configurations, version control, and peer review of infrastructure changes"],"answer":3,"explain":"Infrastructure as Code (IaC) improves security by enabling peer review of changes, enforcing consistent security configurations, detecting drift, and providing audit history of all infrastructure modifications."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What does AWS Config do?","options":["Manages application configuration files stored on EC2 instances", "Records and evaluates AWS resource configurations for compliance and change tracking", "Configures network routing between VPCs and on-premises networks", "Manages configuration of IAM users and their permissions"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Config continuously records resource configuration changes, evaluates them against desired-state rules, and provides a configuration history. It answers 'what did my infrastructure look like at 2pm last Tuesday?'"},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides dedicated, single-tenant hardware security modules (HSMs) for generating and using your own encryption keys?","options":["AWS KMS using shared multi-tenant hardware", "AWS Certificate Manager for SSL/TLS certificate management", "AWS Secrets Manager for application credential storage", "AWS CloudHSM with dedicated single-tenant HSM hardware"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS CloudHSM provides dedicated HSM hardware exclusively for your use. Unlike shared KMS, CloudHSM meets compliance requirements (FIPS 140-2 Level 3) where keys must never leave a dedicated hardware device."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company receives an AWS abuse notification that their EC2 instance is sending spam emails. What should they do first?","options":["Immediately investigate the instance for compromise, isolate it, and respond to AWS abuse team", "Ignore it since AWS may have made an error in detection", "Terminate the instance immediately and file an insurance claim", "Change the security group to block all outbound traffic and continue operations"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS abuse notifications should be taken seriously immediately. Isolate the instance (modify security group, snapshot), investigate for compromise (check processes, logs), remediate, and respond to abuse@amazonaws.com within 24 hours."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the AWS Shared Responsibility Model's customer responsibility for Amazon RDS?","options":["Patching the database engine software and OS", "Ensuring RDS Multi-AZ failover works correctly", "Maintaining physical hardware and hypervisor for RDS instances", "Managing database schema, data encryption, and access control (IAM, security groups)"],"answer":3,"explain":"For RDS, AWS manages OS patching, database engine patching, hardware, and Multi-AZ failover. Customers are responsible for database-level security (user accounts, permissions), data encryption settings, and security group configuration."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which of the following is a customer's responsibility under the shared responsibility model for Amazon EC2?","options":["Maintaining the physical host servers and network hardware", "Providing power, cooling, and physical security for the data center", "Ensuring the hypervisor is secure and properly isolated between instances", "Patching the operating system, managing applications, and configuring security groups"],"answer":3,"explain":"For EC2 (IaaS), customers own the guest OS — they must patch it, secure the applications, manage IAM credentials, configure security groups, and encrypt their data. AWS owns everything below the hypervisor."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to encrypt data in transit between their application and an RDS database. What should they enable?","options":["S3 server-side encryption for data stored in the database", "SSL/TLS encryption for connections between the application and RDS endpoint", "AWS KMS encryption keys for the RDS volume", "VPC peering to prevent traffic from traveling over the public internet"],"answer":1,"explain":"Encryption in transit uses SSL/TLS to encrypt data as it travels between the application and RDS. RDS provides TLS certificates; applications must enable SSL in their connection string."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the purpose of AWS Identity Federation?","options":["Federating multiple AWS accounts under a single organization", "Allowing users from an external identity provider (Active Directory, Google) to access AWS using their existing credentials", "Creating federated IAM policies that apply across all AWS services", "Combining multiple IAM roles into a single federated permission set"],"answer":1,"explain":"Identity federation lets users authenticate with external IdPs (Active Directory, Okta, Google) and receive temporary AWS credentials via STS AssumeRoleWithSAML or OIDC, eliminating duplicate AWS-specific user management."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides a managed, scalable solution for DDoS protection with 24/7 access to the DDoS Response Team?","options":["AWS Shield Standard included automatically for all customers", "AWS Shield Advanced for enhanced DDoS protection with DRT access", "AWS WAF filtering application-layer DDoS attacks", "Amazon CloudFront absorbing volumetric DDoS traffic at edge"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Shield Advanced provides enhanced DDoS detection, near real-time visibility, cost protection for DDoS-related scaling charges, and 24/7 access to the DDoS Response Team (DRT) for incident support."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to ensure only their own encryption keys protect their S3 data, with AWS never having access to the plaintext keys. What option achieves this?","options":["SSE-S3 using AWS-managed keys automatically", "S3 Object Lock preventing key access to AWS", "SSE-KMS using Customer Managed Keys in AWS KMS", "SSE-C — customer-provided encryption keys where the customer controls and stores keys outside AWS"],"answer":3,"explain":"SSE-C (Server-Side Encryption with Customer-Provided Keys) allows customers to provide their own encryption keys with each request. AWS performs the encryption but never stores the key, providing maximum key control."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What AWS feature allows you to define and enforce which regions AWS resources can be created in?","options":["IAM policies with region conditions restricting service access", "AWS Organizations SCPs with region restriction conditions", "AWS Config rules monitoring resource regions", "Both IAM policies and SCPs can enforce region restrictions"],"answer":3,"explain":"Region restrictions can be enforced both through IAM policies (Condition: aws:RequestedRegion) and SCP conditions. SCPs provide organization-wide enforcement that individual account admins cannot override."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the AWS penetration testing policy?","options":["Penetration testing AWS infrastructure is strictly prohibited under all circumstances", "Customers can perform penetration testing on their own AWS resources without prior approval for most services", "Customers must always get written AWS approval before any security testing", "Penetration testing requires Enterprise Support plan subscription"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS allows customers to perform penetration testing on their own AWS resources (EC2, RDS, CloudFront, API Gateway, Lambda, etc.) without prior approval. Testing AWS infrastructure itself or other customers' resources is prohibited."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service integrates with Microsoft Active Directory to provide directory services in the AWS cloud?","options":["AWS Directory Service providing managed Active Directory in AWS", "AWS IAM Identity Center replacing Active Directory", "Amazon Cognito for enterprise directory integration", "AWS Organizations for multi-account directory management"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Directory Service offers managed Microsoft Active Directory (AWS Managed Microsoft AD), Simple AD, and AD Connector for connecting to on-premises AD. It enables EC2 instances to join a domain and use AD authentication."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to meet GDPR requirements for data stored in AWS. What is their primary responsibility?","options":["The customer is responsible for data classification, access controls, processing purposes, and data subject rights management", "AWS is fully responsible for GDPR compliance for all customer data", "GDPR only applies to European AWS regions, not global deployments", "AWS Artifact provides GDPR compliance that covers customer data automatically"],"answer":0,"explain":"GDPR compliance is a shared responsibility. AWS provides compliant infrastructure (certified data centers, data processing agreements). Customers are responsible for their data — what they collect, how they process it, and honoring data subject rights."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the function of AWS Trusted Advisor in the context of security?","options":["Providing managed security operations center services", "Checking AWS configurations against security best practices and flagging risks like open S3 buckets and MFA gaps", "Monitoring for active security threats and intrusion attempts", "Automatically remediating security misconfigurations found in accounts"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Trusted Advisor analyzes AWS configurations and provides recommendations across security, cost, performance, fault tolerance, and service limits. Security checks include open security groups, public S3 buckets, and missing MFA."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs a scalable object storage solution for storing millions of images with 99.999999999% durability. Which service should they use?","options":["Amazon EBS block storage attached to EC2 instances", "Amazon EFS elastic file system for shared storage", "Amazon S3 object storage with eleven 9s of durability", "Amazon Glacier for long-term archival storage"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon S3 provides 99.999999999% (11 nines) of durability by redundantly storing data across multiple AZs. It's designed for unlimited scalability and is the standard for object storage in AWS."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to run a web server without managing the operating system, patching, or scaling. Which AWS service best fits?","options":["Amazon EC2 with auto-managed OS patching", "Amazon ECS running containers on managed EC2 clusters", "AWS Elastic Beanstalk deploying applications without managing underlying infrastructure", "Amazon Lightsail for simple VPS management"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Elastic Beanstalk is a PaaS that automatically handles deployment, capacity provisioning, load balancing, auto-scaling, and health monitoring. You upload code and Beanstalk manages the infrastructure."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which EC2 pricing model offers up to 90% discount for fault-tolerant workloads that can tolerate interruption?","options":["On-Demand Instances with per-second billing", "Reserved Instances with 1 or 3-year commitment", "Spot Instances using spare EC2 capacity at discounted prices", "Dedicated Hosts for compliance and licensing requirements"],"answer":2,"explain":"EC2 Spot Instances use spare AWS capacity at up to 90% discount. AWS can reclaim Spot Instances with a 2-minute warning. Ideal for batch processing, data analysis, and fault-tolerant workloads that can checkpoint and resume."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company runs a database that requires consistent compute performance 24/7 for the next 3 years. Which pricing model provides the lowest cost?","options":["On-Demand Instances for maximum flexibility", "Spot Instances for maximum discount", "Reserved Instances with 3-year All Upfront payment", "Savings Plans with compute flexibility"],"answer":2,"explain":"Reserved Instances with a 3-year all-upfront commitment provide the maximum discount (up to 72% off On-Demand) for steady-state workloads with predictable usage. All-upfront maximizes savings vs monthly or partial upfront."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides managed relational databases with automated backups, Multi-AZ failover, and no OS management?","options":["Amazon DynamoDB for NoSQL database management", "Amazon Aurora for cloud-native relational databases only", "Amazon Redshift for data warehousing", "Amazon RDS for managed relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc.)"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon RDS manages relational database engines (MySQL, PostgreSQL, MariaDB, Oracle, SQL Server, Aurora) with automated backups, point-in-time recovery, Multi-AZ high availability, and automated patching."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A startup needs a NoSQL database that can handle millions of requests per second with single-digit millisecond latency. Which service is best?","options":["Amazon DynamoDB fully managed NoSQL with consistent single-digit ms performance", "Amazon RDS MySQL with read replicas for scaling", "Amazon ElastiCache Redis for in-memory caching", "Amazon Neptune for graph database workloads"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon DynamoDB is a fully managed serverless NoSQL database delivering consistent single-digit millisecond performance at any scale, from zero to millions of requests per second with no capacity planning required."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Lambda and what problem does it solve?","options":["A container orchestration service replacing traditional server management", "A serverless compute service running code in response to events without provisioning servers", "A managed virtual machine service with automatic OS patching", "A function as a service only for machine learning workloads"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Lambda runs code triggered by events (API calls, S3 uploads, DynamoDB changes) without servers to manage. You pay only per invocation and execution time (100ms increments), scaling automatically from 0 to thousands of concurrent executions."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs to distribute HTTP/HTTPS traffic across multiple EC2 instances with health checks and SSL termination. Which service provides this?","options":["Amazon Route 53 for DNS-based load balancing", "Classic Load Balancer for legacy EC2-Classic workloads", "Network Load Balancer (NLB) for ultra-low latency TCP/UDP", "Application Load Balancer (ALB) for Layer 7 HTTP/HTTPS routing"],"answer":3,"explain":"ALB operates at Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS), providing path-based and host-based routing, SSL termination, sticky sessions, and WebSocket support. It integrates with EC2, ECS, Lambda, and supports content-based routing."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon VPC and why is it important?","options":["A virtual private cloud for connecting on-premises networks to AWS directly", "A private CDN service for internal application content delivery", "A VPN service providing encrypted connectivity between offices and AWS", "An isolated virtual network in AWS where you control IP ranges, subnets, routing, and security"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon VPC provides an isolated network environment in AWS where you define IP address ranges (CIDR blocks), subnets, route tables, internet gateways, and security controls. Resources in VPC are logically isolated from other customers."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which S3 storage class is designed for infrequently accessed data that still needs millisecond retrieval, at lower cost than S3 Standard?","options":["S3 Standard for frequently accessed data", "S3 Standard-IA (Infrequent Access) for less frequent access with instant retrieval", "S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval for archival with 1-12 hour retrieval", "S3 Intelligent-Tiering automatically moving data between tiers"],"answer":1,"explain":"S3 Standard-IA charges lower storage prices than S3 Standard but adds a per-GB retrieval fee. It's ideal for backups and disaster recovery data accessed monthly, with the same durability and instant retrieval as Standard."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to run containerized applications without managing EC2 instances or clusters. Which service provides serverless containers?","options":["Amazon ECS on EC2 launch type managing your own cluster", "AWS Fargate running containers without managing underlying servers", "Amazon EKS managing Kubernetes control plane only", "AWS Batch for containerized batch processing jobs"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Fargate is a serverless compute engine for containers that removes the need to provision or manage EC2 instances. You define CPU/memory requirements and Fargate handles the infrastructure, scaling, and availability."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a petabyte-scale data warehouse for running complex analytical queries?","options":["Amazon Redshift for petabyte-scale data warehousing and analytics", "Amazon RDS for transactional relational database queries", "Amazon DynamoDB for NoSQL analytical workloads", "Amazon Aurora for fast cloud-native database queries"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon Redshift is a fully managed data warehouse that can query petabytes of structured and semi-structured data using standard SQL. It uses columnar storage and MPP (massively parallel processing) for fast analytical queries."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon CloudWatch and what can you do with it?","options":["A security service monitoring for unauthorized AWS API calls", "A cost management service tracking AWS spending in real time", "A monitoring and observability service for AWS resources providing metrics, logs, and alarms", "A deployment service tracking application release versions"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon CloudWatch collects metrics, logs, and events from AWS services and applications. You can create dashboards, set alarms (CPU > 80% → scale out), collect custom application logs, and trigger automated responses."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to run their application code without any server management and pay only when their code executes. This describes which model?","options":["IaaS — Infrastructure as a Service with managed VMs", "CaaS — Containers as a Service on managed Kubernetes", "PaaS — Platform as a Service with managed runtime", "Serverless computing using Lambda for event-driven execution"],"answer":3,"explain":"Serverless computing (Lambda) runs code only when triggered by events, scales automatically from zero to massive scale, and charges per invocation + duration. No servers, no patches, no capacity planning required."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a fully managed message queue for decoupling application components?","options":["Amazon SNS for publish/subscribe notifications", "Amazon SQS for reliable message queuing between services", "Amazon EventBridge for event-driven architecture routing", "Amazon Kinesis for real-time streaming data processing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon SQS provides managed message queues for decoupling producers from consumers. Messages are stored durably until processed. SQS enables microservices to communicate without direct dependencies."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to send notifications to millions of subscribers across email, SMS, and mobile push simultaneously. Which service enables this?","options":["Amazon SQS for reliable message delivery to queues", "Amazon SES for transactional email delivery", "Amazon SNS for pub/sub notifications to multiple subscribers across multiple protocols", "Amazon Pinpoint for targeted customer communication campaigns"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon SNS is a managed pub/sub messaging service that fans out messages to multiple subscribers simultaneously via email, SMS, HTTP, SQS queues, and Lambda functions, supporting millions of subscribers."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Route 53 and what does it do?","options":["A scalable DNS web service for domain registration, routing, and health checking", "A content delivery network caching web content globally", "A load balancer distributing traffic across EC2 instances", "A VPN service providing secure connectivity to AWS VPCs"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon Route 53 provides DNS registration and resolution with routing policies (latency, geolocation, weighted, failover) and health checks. It integrates with AWS services for seamless DNS management."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides managed Kubernetes for running containerized applications?","options":["Amazon EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service) for managed Kubernetes clusters", "AWS Fargate for serverless container execution", "Amazon ECS for AWS-native container orchestration", "AWS App Runner for fully managed containerized web apps"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon EKS manages the Kubernetes control plane (API server, etcd) across multiple AZs, handling upgrades and patching. You manage worker nodes (EC2 or Fargate) and deploy standard Kubernetes workloads."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs to migrate a large amount of data (100TB) from on-premises to S3 but has limited internet bandwidth. Which service helps?","options":["AWS Snowball Edge physical device for offline data migration", "AWS Direct Connect providing dedicated 10Gbps connection", "Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration for faster uploads", "AWS DataSync for network-based transfer optimization"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Snowball Edge is a physical device shipped to your location. You copy data to it and ship it back to AWS, which loads it into S3. For 100TB with limited bandwidth, this is faster and cheaper than network transfer."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides dedicated, high-bandwidth private network connectivity between on-premises and AWS?","options":["AWS VPN using encrypted tunnels over the internet", "AWS Transit Gateway connecting VPCs and on-premises networks", "Amazon Route 53 for DNS-based routing to AWS", "AWS Direct Connect providing dedicated private network connections"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Direct Connect establishes dedicated 1Gbps-100Gbps private network connections from on-premises to AWS, bypassing the public internet for consistent performance, lower latency, and reduced data transfer costs."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon ElastiCache used for?","options":["In-memory caching using Redis or Memcached to speed up database-backed applications", "Caching CloudFront content at edge locations globally", "Caching Lambda function results for faster serverless execution", "Storing application configuration caches in a managed key-value store"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon ElastiCache provides managed in-memory Redis and Memcached clusters. Applications cache frequently accessed data from RDS/DynamoDB in memory, reducing database load and achieving sub-millisecond read performance."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS CloudFormation used for?","options":["Monitoring cloud resources and setting performance alarms", "Tracking configuration changes to AWS resources over time", "Managing software deployments to EC2 instances and containers", "Infrastructure as Code — defining and provisioning AWS resources using JSON or YAML templates"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS CloudFormation allows you to model and provision AWS infrastructure using templates (JSON/YAML). A single template can create VPCs, EC2 instances, RDS databases, and IAM roles, enabling repeatable, version-controlled infrastructure."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company runs a critical application on EC2 and wants to ensure it continues running even if an entire AWS Availability Zone fails. What should they implement?","options":["Use a larger EC2 instance type with more redundant hardware", "Use Reserved Instances for guaranteed instance availability", "Enable EC2 instance recovery for automatic restart after failure", "Deploy EC2 instances across multiple Availability Zones behind a load balancer"],"answer":3,"explain":"Deploying across multiple AZs with an Elastic Load Balancer ensures the application continues running if one AZ fails. The load balancer routes traffic only to healthy instances in operational AZs."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service is a managed, serverless data integration service for discovering, preparing, and combining data for analytics?","options":["AWS Glue for serverless ETL and data catalog", "Amazon Redshift for data warehousing workloads", "Amazon EMR for big data processing with Spark and Hadoop", "Amazon Kinesis for real-time streaming data ingestion"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Glue is a serverless ETL service with a Data Catalog that discovers schemas, crawls data sources, and transforms data for analytics. No servers to manage — pay only for compute used during job runs."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Aurora and how does it differ from standard RDS?","options":["Aurora is Amazon's NoSQL database optimized for key-value workloads", "Aurora is a data warehouse service competing with Redshift for analytics", "Aurora is a cloud-native relational database with up to 5x MySQL and 3x PostgreSQL performance, MySQL/PostgreSQL compatible", "Aurora is identical to standard RDS but uses proprietary storage hardware"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon Aurora is a cloud-native relational database built from scratch for AWS, providing up to 5x MySQL and 3x PostgreSQL performance through distributed storage replication across 6 copies in 3 AZs, with MySQL/PostgreSQL compatibility."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is the primary use case for Amazon Kinesis Data Streams?","options":["Storing and querying large datasets for business intelligence", "Real-time ingestion and processing of streaming data (logs, clickstreams, IoT)", "Batch processing of large datasets on a scheduled basis", "Message queuing for decoupling microservice applications"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Kinesis Data Streams ingests and processes real-time streaming data at massive scale. Use cases include clickstream analytics, application logs, IoT telemetry, and financial transaction processing with sub-second latency."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a managed Apache Kafka-compatible message streaming service?","options":["Amazon SQS for reliable message queue processing", "Amazon MSK (Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka) for Kafka workloads", "Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for real-time streaming", "Amazon EventBridge for event-driven architecture"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon MSK (Managed Streaming for Apache Kafka) provisions and manages Kafka clusters, handling broker provisioning, patching, and availability. It's compatible with existing Kafka applications and tools."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to build a RESTful API for their mobile app with authentication, throttling, and caching. Which AWS service manages this?","options":["AWS AppSync for GraphQL API management", "Amazon API Gateway for RESTful and WebSocket API management", "AWS Lambda URL for direct function invocation via HTTP", "Elastic Load Balancer for HTTP request routing"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon API Gateway creates, publishes, maintains, and secures RESTful and WebSocket APIs. It provides authentication (Cognito, Lambda authorizers), throttling, caching, request/response transformation, and SDK generation."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What does Amazon S3 Versioning provide?","options":["Preserving, retrieving, and restoring every version of every object stored in a bucket", "Automatically optimizing S3 storage costs by moving objects between tiers", "Creating synchronized copies of S3 buckets across multiple regions", "Encrypting all S3 objects automatically when versioning is enabled"],"answer":0,"explain":"S3 Versioning maintains multiple versions of an object, protecting against accidental deletions and overwrites. You can restore previous versions, and MFA Delete adds extra protection against accidental version deletion."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS compute service is best for running scheduled batch jobs that process large datasets overnight?","options":["AWS Lambda for event-driven serverless execution", "Amazon EC2 with scheduled Auto Scaling policies", "AWS Batch for fully managed batch computing workloads", "Amazon ECS for containerized application workloads"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Batch dynamically provisions optimal compute resources (EC2, Spot, Fargate) for batch jobs based on volume and requirements. It handles job scheduling, dependency management, and scales to hundreds of thousands of jobs."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to provide a shared file system accessible by multiple EC2 instances simultaneously across Availability Zones. Which service provides this?","options":["Amazon EBS volumes attached to single EC2 instances", "Amazon FSx for Windows File Server for SMB protocol access", "Amazon S3 for object storage accessible from EC2 via API", "Amazon EFS (Elastic File System) for shared NFS file storage across multiple AZs"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon EFS is a managed NFS file system that automatically grows and shrinks, accessible simultaneously from multiple EC2 instances across multiple AZs. It's perfect for shared content repositories and CMS workloads."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon CloudFront's primary function?","options":["Providing DNS resolution and domain registration globally", "A global CDN that delivers content with low latency by caching at 400+ edge locations", "A load balancing service distributing traffic across EC2 instances", "A network monitoring service tracking inter-region data transfer"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon CloudFront caches content at 400+ global edge locations, serving it to users from the nearest location. This dramatically reduces latency for websites, APIs, video streaming, and software downloads."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides machine learning-powered search capabilities for websites and applications?","options":["Amazon Comprehend for NLP text analysis", "Amazon Kendra for intelligent ML-powered enterprise search", "Amazon Elasticsearch Service for text search workloads", "Amazon CloudSearch for managed search service"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Kendra uses ML to provide intelligent enterprise search, understanding natural language queries to find accurate answers from documents, FAQs, and knowledge bases rather than just keyword matching."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company needs to analyze their existing workloads to identify which EC2 instances to right-size before migrating to AWS. Which service provides this?","options":["AWS Pricing Calculator estimating costs before migration", "AWS Migration Hub for tracking migration progress", "AWS Compute Optimizer recommending optimal EC2 instance types", "AWS Application Discovery Service collecting on-premises server data"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Compute Optimizer uses ML to analyze historical utilization metrics and recommends optimal EC2 instance types, Auto Scaling groups, EBS volumes, and Lambda memory to reduce costs and improve performance."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon SES (Simple Email Service) used for?","options":["Managing team communication and notifications within AWS", "Setting up corporate email servers for employees", "Securing email communications with end-to-end encryption", "Sending bulk transactional and marketing emails at scale with high deliverability"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon SES is a cost-effective email sending service for transactional emails (order confirmations, password resets), bulk marketing campaigns, and automated notifications at scale with high deliverability."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What does Amazon S3 Transfer Acceleration provide?","options":["Accelerating data processing speed for S3-stored files", "Parallel upload of S3 objects for improved throughput", "Automatic compression of files before uploading to S3", "Faster S3 uploads from clients worldwide using CloudFront edge locations and AWS backbone"],"answer":3,"explain":"S3 Transfer Acceleration routes uploads through the nearest CloudFront edge location, then uses AWS's private network backbone to transfer to S3. This can improve upload speeds by 50-500% for distant users."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which service provides automated deployment pipelines for continuous integration and delivery (CI/CD) on AWS?","options":["AWS CloudFormation for infrastructure deployment automation", "AWS Elastic Beanstalk for application deployment management", "AWS Systems Manager for operational automation", "AWS CodePipeline for orchestrating CI/CD workflows"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS CodePipeline orchestrates CI/CD pipelines connecting source (CodeCommit, GitHub), build (CodeBuild), and deploy (CodeDeploy, Elastic Beanstalk, ECS) stages for automated software release processes."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Auto Scaling and what problem does it solve?","options":["Automatically upgrading EC2 instance types to handle more capacity", "Automatically adjusting the number of EC2 instances or other resources based on demand", "Automatically scaling IAM permissions as user roles change", "Automatically scaling S3 storage capacity as more objects are added"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Auto Scaling adds instances when demand increases (scale out) and removes them when demand decreases (scale in), matching capacity to actual load. This maintains performance during peaks and minimizes costs during low demand."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Elastic Block Store (EBS) primarily used for?","options":["Object storage for files, images, and backups accessible via HTTP", "Persistent block storage volumes attached to EC2 instances for OS and application data", "Shared file storage accessible from multiple EC2 instances simultaneously", "Archival storage for data accessed infrequently"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon EBS provides persistent block storage volumes that attach to EC2 instances like virtual hard drives. Unlike instance store, EBS persists after instance stop/termination. Used for OS volumes, databases, and application data."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company wants to quickly set up a virtual desktop for remote employees without managing physical desktops or VDI infrastructure. Which AWS service helps?","options":["Amazon AppStream 2.0 for streaming individual applications", "AWS Client VPN for secure remote network access", "Amazon WorkSpaces for managed virtual desktop infrastructure", "Amazon EC2 with Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP)"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon WorkSpaces provides managed cloud desktops (Windows or Linux) accessible from anywhere. AWS manages the infrastructure, patching, and backup. Employees connect via the WorkSpaces client from any device."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service enables running SQL queries directly on data stored in S3 without loading it into a database?","options":["Amazon Athena for serverless SQL queries directly on S3 data", "Amazon RDS with S3 integration for external tables", "Amazon Redshift Spectrum for S3 data querying", "AWS Glue ETL for transforming S3 data before querying"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon Athena is a serverless interactive query service that runs standard SQL directly on data in S3 (CSV, JSON, Parquet, ORC) with no infrastructure to manage. Pay only per query based on data scanned."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is the benefit of using Amazon RDS Multi-AZ deployment?","options":["Improved read performance by distributing queries across multiple databases", "Reduced storage costs by compressing data across multiple availability zones", "Automatic failover to a standby replica in another AZ for high availability during failures", "Automatic scaling of read capacity based on query volume"],"answer":2,"explain":"RDS Multi-AZ synchronously replicates data to a standby instance in a different AZ. If the primary fails, RDS automatically fails over to the standby (typically within 1-2 minutes) without manual intervention."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Step Functions used for?","options":["Sequencing Lambda functions in a serverless application automatically", "Monitoring the steps of a database migration from on-premises to AWS", "Managing step-by-step deployment pipelines for application releases", "Orchestrating distributed applications and microservices into visual workflows"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Step Functions provides serverless workflow orchestration, coordinating multiple Lambda functions, ECS tasks, and AWS services into visual state machines with error handling, retries, and parallel execution."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a globally distributed in-memory cache to reduce latency for DynamoDB tables?","options":["Amazon ElastiCache Redis in front of DynamoDB", "AWS Global Accelerator routing DynamoDB requests globally", "Amazon CloudFront caching DynamoDB query results", "Amazon DAX (DynamoDB Accelerator) providing microsecond read performance"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon DAX is a fully managed, in-memory cache specifically for DynamoDB, providing microsecond response times for read-heavy workloads. It's API-compatible with DynamoDB, requiring minimal code changes."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS pricing model has no upfront costs and charges by the hour or second with no long-term commitments?","options":["On-Demand pricing with pay-as-you-go billing", "Reserved Instances with upfront payment commitment", "Spot Instances with variable pricing based on capacity", "Dedicated Hosts with fixed monthly reservation fees"],"answer":0,"explain":"On-Demand pricing charges for compute, storage, and data transfer without upfront fees or minimum commitments. You pay only for what you use, making it ideal for unpredictable workloads and short-term experiments."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company has multiple AWS accounts. How can they consolidate billing and receive volume discounts across all accounts?","options":["Use AWS Organizations with consolidated billing to combine usage across all accounts", "Contact AWS Sales to negotiate multi-account pricing", "Create a single AWS account and share access across teams", "Enable AWS Cost Explorer across all accounts for unified billing"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Organizations consolidated billing aggregates usage across all linked accounts into a single bill. Combined usage may qualify for volume tier pricing discounts on services like S3 and data transfer."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which free AWS tool estimates monthly AWS costs before deploying resources?","options":["AWS Pricing Calculator for estimating future AWS costs", "AWS Cost Explorer analyzing historical spending trends", "AWS Budgets for setting spending alerts on current usage", "AWS Trusted Advisor checking for cost optimization opportunities"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Pricing Calculator is a free web-based tool for estimating monthly AWS bills before deployment. Configure services, quantities, and regions to get detailed cost breakdowns for planning and budgeting."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS service allows you to set custom cost and usage budgets with alerts when spending exceeds thresholds?","options":["AWS Budgets for proactive cost and usage alerts", "AWS Cost Explorer visualizing historical spending", "AWS Cost and Usage Report for detailed billing data", "AWS Pricing Calculator for estimating future costs"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Budgets lets you define budget thresholds for cost, usage, and Reserved Instance coverage. Alert notifications (email, SNS) trigger when actual or forecasted spending exceeds defined thresholds."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What does the AWS Free Tier provide?","options":["Unlimited free access to all AWS services for new customers", "Limited free usage of specific AWS services for 12 months, some always free, and some trial offers", "A permanent discount of 50% for startups using AWS", "Free usage of all AWS services if monthly spending stays under $100"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Free Tier has three types: 12-month free (EC2 750hr/month, S3 5GB), Always Free (Lambda 1M requests/month, DynamoDB 25GB), and Trials (limited-time service trials). Exceeding limits incurs standard charges."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company notices a large unexpected AWS bill. Which service provides a detailed breakdown of costs by service, region, and tag?","options":["AWS Budgets for budget threshold management", "AWS Cost Explorer for interactive cost visualization and analysis", "AWS Cost and Usage Report for granular hourly billing data", "AWS Trusted Advisor for cost optimization recommendations"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Cost Explorer provides interactive charts and graphs to analyze spending by service, region, linked account, and tags. It identifies cost trends, anomalies, and forecasts future spending based on historical patterns."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which pricing model offers flexibility to change instance types within a family while still receiving discounts compared to On-Demand?","options":["Standard Reserved Instances locked to a specific instance type", "Convertible Reserved Instances allowing instance type changes within commitment", "Compute Savings Plans for maximum flexibility across instance families", "Spot Instances with dynamic pricing based on capacity"],"answer":2,"explain":"Compute Savings Plans (not Convertible RIs) offer the most flexibility — they apply to any EC2 instance type, region, OS, and tenancy. Convertible RIs allow exchanges within the same family but require manual exchange requests."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is AWS Cost Allocation Tags used for?","options":["Categorizing AWS resources to track costs by project, department, or environment in billing reports", "Automatically tagging resources for compliance requirements", "Setting cost limits on tagged resources to prevent overspending", "Tagging resources for security group assignments in VPCs"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cost allocation tags (user-defined or AWS-generated) appear in billing reports, enabling cost breakdown by business dimension. Tag by project, team, or environment (prod/dev/test) to allocate costs and optimize spending."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is included in AWS data transfer pricing?","options":["Data transfer OUT from AWS to the internet is charged; data transfer IN is typically free", "Data transfer into AWS from the internet is always charged", "Data transfer between AWS services in the same region is always charged", "All data transfer is included in the base service price"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS charges for data transferred OUT from AWS to the internet (first 100GB/month free, then tiered pricing). Data transfer IN from the internet is free. Transfer between services in the same AZ is often free; across AZs has a small charge."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A startup wants to reduce EC2 costs by committing to a consistent compute spend for 1 year. Which pricing option provides broad flexibility across instance types?","options":["Compute Savings Plans for flexible savings across any EC2 instance type", "EC2 Reserved Instances for specific instance type discounts", "EC2 Spot Instances for variable workload cost reduction", "Dedicated Hosts for compliance and licensing optimization"],"answer":0,"explain":"Compute Savings Plans commit to a consistent hourly spend (e.g., $10/hr) for 1 or 3 years, applying discounts automatically to any EC2 instance type, family, region, OS, or tenancy — far more flexible than RIs."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS service provides a detailed, granular billing report with hourly or daily line items for every AWS service usage?","options":["AWS Cost Explorer for interactive spending visualization", "AWS Budgets for threshold-based cost monitoring", "AWS Cost and Usage Report (CUR) for comprehensive billing data", "AWS Pricing Calculator for future cost estimation"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Cost and Usage Report delivers the most detailed billing data available — hourly or daily line items for every service, resource ID, pricing details, and cost allocation tags, delivered to S3 for custom analysis."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company wants AWS to automatically alert them if their bill is forecasted to exceed $1,000 this month before they actually overspend. Which tool enables this?","options":["AWS Cost Explorer showing historical trends", "AWS Trusted Advisor reviewing cost optimization opportunities", "AWS Pricing Calculator estimating costs upfront", "AWS Budgets with forecasted cost alerts"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Budgets can send alerts when forecasted costs are projected to exceed your budget threshold, giving you time to take action before the bill is finalized rather than after charges have been incurred."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is the AWS Support plan that provides production system impaired response within 4 hours?","options":["Basic Support — free tier with no production SLAs", "Developer Support — business hours email support only", "Business Support — 24/7 phone/chat with 4-hour production impaired response", "Enterprise Support — 15-minute critical system down response"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Business Support provides 24/7 phone/chat/email support with response times of: 4 hours for production system impaired, 1 hour for production system down, and 24 business hours for general guidance."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What AWS service provides recommendations to reduce EC2 costs by identifying idle and underutilized instances?","options":["AWS Config checking resource configuration compliance", "AWS Cost Explorer Reserved Instance recommendations", "AWS Trusted Advisor identifying cost optimization opportunities", "AWS Compute Optimizer right-sizing recommendations"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Trusted Advisor checks for idle EC2 instances, unattached EBS volumes, and underutilized RDS instances. AWS Compute Optimizer complements this with ML-based right-sizing recommendations for optimal instance types."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company purchases Reserved Instances for EC2 but their usage pattern changes and the RIs no longer align with their workload. What can they do?","options":["Contact AWS to cancel the Reserved Instances immediately", "Sell unused Reserved Instances on the AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace", "Convert Reserved Instances to On-Demand automatically", "Transfer Reserved Instances between AWS accounts for free"],"answer":1,"explain":"The AWS Reserved Instance Marketplace allows customers to sell their unused Standard Reserved Instances to other AWS customers. This provides an exit option when workloads change and RIs no longer match usage."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS service enables you to view and manage all of your AWS costs from a single, integrated view even across multiple payer accounts?","options":["AWS Cost Explorer for a single account cost analysis", "AWS Cost and Usage Report for detailed billing data export", "AWS Cost Management console providing unified cost visibility", "AWS Organizations for multi-account consolidated billing view"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Cost Management console (including Cost Explorer, Budgets, Cost and Usage Reports) provides unified visibility across all linked accounts in AWS Organizations, enabling cross-account cost analysis and optimization."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"How is Amazon S3 storage pricing structured?","options":["Flat monthly fee regardless of amount stored", "Annual commitment pricing with reserved storage capacity", "Pay per GB stored per month, plus charges for requests and data transfer out", "Free storage up to 1TB, then per-GB pricing above that"],"answer":2,"explain":"S3 pricing has multiple components: storage (per GB/month varying by storage class), requests (PUT, GET per 1000 requests), data retrieval (for IA/Glacier classes), and data transfer out to internet."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company wants to track how much each team is spending on AWS. What is the best practice for cost attribution?","options":["Create separate AWS accounts for each team", "Ask teams to self-report their AWS resource usage monthly", "Review monthly bills manually and estimate team costs", "Use consistent cost allocation tags (e.g., team=engineering) on all resources and activate them in billing"],"answer":3,"explain":"Consistent cost allocation tagging is the scalable best practice. Tag every resource with team, project, and environment tags, activate them in billing preferences, and filter Cost Explorer by tag to see per-team spending."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is AWS Lambda's pricing model?","options":["Per-hour pricing based on memory configuration", "Per-invocation plus per-millisecond of execution time based on memory allocated", "Monthly fixed pricing based on maximum concurrent executions", "Per-GB of data processed by Lambda functions"],"answer":1,"explain":"Lambda charges per request ($0.20 per 1M requests) plus per GB-second of compute time (duration × memory). The first 1M requests and 400,000 GB-seconds per month are always free, making Lambda very cost-effective for low-volume workloads."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS tool can help identify which EC2 Reserved Instances are underutilized and recommend purchasing options?","options":["AWS Pricing Calculator for evaluating purchase options", "AWS Budgets tracking RI coverage percentage", "AWS Trusted Advisor checking RI utilization rates", "AWS Cost Explorer with RI utilization and coverage reports"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Cost Explorer provides Reserved Instance utilization reports (how much of your RI capacity was actually used) and coverage reports (what percentage of your usage was covered by RIs), plus purchase recommendations."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"A company is choosing between AWS and building their own data center. Which total cost of ownership (TCO) factors favor AWS?","options":["AWS eliminates server hardware purchase, data center facility costs, power/cooling, and staff for infrastructure management", "AWS always costs less than on-premises for every workload", "On-premises is always cheaper for steady-state workloads with predictable demand", "AWS pricing is transparent while on-premises has no hidden costs"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS TCO advantages include: no capital expenditure on hardware, no facility costs, no power/cooling expenses, no hardware lifecycle management, and reduced staff for infrastructure. AWS TCO Calculator quantifies these savings."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What does 'pay for what you use' mean in AWS pricing?","options":["Pay a flat fee covering all possible AWS service usage", "AWS bills annually based on estimated usage projections", "Pay monthly regardless of actual usage to reserve capacity", "Charges are based only on actual resource consumption — no minimum fees or upfront costs required"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS's fundamental pricing principle charges only for resources consumed: EC2 per second/hour running, S3 per GB stored, Lambda per invocation. When you stop using a resource, billing stops. No idle capacity charges."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"Which AWS Support plan includes Infrastructure Event Management for major launches and migrations at no additional cost?","options":["Business Support included in standard pricing", "Enterprise On-Ramp for production workloads", "Developer Support for growing companies", "Enterprise Support providing proactive engagement including IEM"],"answer":3,"explain":"Enterprise Support includes Infrastructure Event Management (IEM), where AWS Solution Architects provide hands-on operational guidance for significant events like product launches, migrations, and high-traffic events."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What are the 6 R's of cloud migration strategies? Which strategy involves rehosting an application without changes?","options":["Rehost (lift-and-shift) — moving the application to cloud with no changes", "Refactor — redesigning the application to be cloud-native", "Replatform — making minor optimizations without changing core architecture", "Retire — decommissioning applications that are no longer needed"],"answer":0,"explain":"Rehost (lift-and-shift) moves applications to the cloud as-is with no code changes. It's the fastest migration approach, ideal for quickly getting out of a data center. Other Rs: Replatform, Refactor, Repurchase, Retire, Retain."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants to replace their self-managed CRM with Salesforce on AWS. Which migration strategy is this?","options":["Rehost — moving existing CRM to EC2 without changes", "Replatform — upgrading the database engine during migration", "Repurchase — dropping the current app and switching to a different SaaS product", "Refactor — rebuilding the CRM as cloud-native microservices"],"answer":2,"explain":"Repurchase (drop-and-shop) means abandoning the current application and purchasing a commercial off-the-shelf SaaS replacement like Salesforce, ServiceNow, or Workday. No migration of the old code needed."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the AWS Cloud Adoption Framework (AWS CAF) used for?","options":["A cost calculator for estimating AWS migration expenses", "A compliance tool for regulated industries migrating to AWS", "A framework providing guidance across 6 perspectives to help organizations plan cloud adoption", "A set of CloudFormation templates for common architecture patterns"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS CAF provides structured guidance across 6 perspectives: Business, People, Governance, Platform, Security, and Operations. It helps organizations identify gaps and create a comprehensive cloud adoption roadmap."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is Recovery Time Objective (RTO) in disaster recovery?","options":["The maximum data loss measured in time that a business can tolerate", "The minimum time required to back up data before a disaster", "The maximum acceptable time to restore a system after a disaster occurs", "The time interval between automatic database backups"],"answer":2,"explain":"RTO is the maximum time a business can be down before it causes unacceptable consequences. Lower RTO = more expensive architecture. AWS services like Route 53 failover and RDS Multi-AZ help achieve low RTO."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is Recovery Point Objective (RPO) in disaster recovery?","options":["The maximum time allowed for system recovery after a failure", "The geographic distance between primary and disaster recovery sites", "The maximum acceptable amount of data loss measured in time", "The minimum number of replicas needed for fault tolerance"],"answer":2,"explain":"RPO is the maximum age of data that can be lost during a disaster. If RPO=1 hour, you need backups every hour. AWS S3 replication, RDS automated backups, and DynamoDB point-in-time recovery help achieve low RPO."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which disaster recovery strategy offers the fastest recovery time but highest cost, by keeping a fully operational duplicate environment always running?","options":["Backup and Restore — cheapest but slowest, restore from backup when needed", "Pilot Light — minimal critical systems always running, scale up when needed", "Warm Standby — scaled-down but fully functional version always running", "Multi-Site Active/Active — full production capacity in multiple regions simultaneously"],"answer":3,"explain":"Multi-Site Active/Active runs full production in multiple AWS regions simultaneously. Failover is instant (near-zero RTO/RPO) but costs 2x since you run full infrastructure in multiple regions. Most expensive DR strategy."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company wants the cheapest disaster recovery strategy and can tolerate several hours of downtime. Which approach should they use?","options":["Multi-Site Active/Active for zero downtime", "Warm Standby with a scaled-down live environment", "Pilot Light with only core database systems running", "Backup and Restore — back up data to S3 and restore EC2 instances when needed"],"answer":3,"explain":"Backup and Restore is the cheapest DR strategy: back up data to S3 or AMI snapshots. During disaster, provision new resources from scratch. Recovery takes hours but costs near zero when not in use."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS service helps track the cost of AWS resources by assigning metadata labels to resources for cost allocation?","options":["AWS Budgets setting spending alerts", "AWS Trusted Advisor recommending cost optimizations", "AWS Cost Explorer analyzing spending patterns", "Cost allocation tags identifying and tracking resource costs by project or team"],"answer":3,"explain":"Cost allocation tags are key-value pairs (e.g., Project=Analytics, Team=Engineering) attached to AWS resources. After activation in Billing, they appear in Cost Explorer and detailed billing reports for granular cost tracking."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What does a Total Cost of Ownership (TCO) analysis help a company evaluate?","options":["The cost of purchasing AWS Reserved Instances vs On-Demand", "The cost difference between AWS and other cloud providers", "The monthly AWS bill breakdown by service and region", "The full comparison of on-premises infrastructure costs vs AWS cloud costs including hidden expenses"],"answer":3,"explain":"TCO analysis compares ALL costs of on-premises (hardware, power, cooling, space, staff, maintenance, depreciation) vs AWS. The AWS Pricing Calculator and Migration Evaluator help build TCO analyses showing true cost comparison."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS Support plan is the minimum required to get 24/7 phone and chat access to Cloud Support Engineers?","options":["Basic Support — free but limited to documentation and forums", "Developer Support — business hours email support only", "Business Support — 24/7 phone and chat with Cloud Support Engineers", "Enterprise Support — dedicated TAM plus 24/7 support"],"answer":2,"explain":"Business Support (from $100/month) is the minimum plan with 24/7 phone and chat access to AWS Cloud Support Engineers. Developer Support only provides business hours email. Enterprise adds a dedicated TAM."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What response time SLA does Business Support provide for production system down cases?","options":["24 hours — next business day response", "12 hours — same day business hours response", "4 hours — urgent response for impaired production systems", "1 hour — for production system down cases"],"answer":3,"explain":"Business Support guarantees: <1 hour for production system DOWN, <4 hours for production IMPAIRED, <12 hours for general guidance. Enterprise Support offers <15 minutes for business-critical systems down."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS tool provides automated recommendations across cost, performance, security, fault tolerance, and service limits?","options":["AWS Config checking configuration compliance against rules", "AWS Well-Architected Tool for structured architecture review", "AWS Trusted Advisor providing real-time best practice recommendations", "Amazon CloudWatch monitoring metrics and setting alarms"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Trusted Advisor inspects your AWS environment and provides actionable recommendations in 5 categories: Cost Optimization, Performance, Security, Fault Tolerance, and Service Limits. Business/Enterprise plans get full checks."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What are the 5 pillars of the AWS Well-Architected Framework?","options":["Cost, Speed, Security, Scale, and Availability", "Operational Excellence, Security, Reliability, Performance Efficiency, and Cost Optimization", "Compute, Storage, Network, Database, and Security", "Design, Build, Test, Deploy, and Monitor"],"answer":1,"explain":"The 5 pillars: Operational Excellence (run and improve operations), Security (protect systems and data), Reliability (recover from failures), Performance Efficiency (use resources efficiently), Cost Optimization (avoid unnecessary costs). A 6th pillar, Sustainability, was added in 2021."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the purpose of AWS Compute Optimizer?","options":["Automatically scaling EC2 instances based on CPU usage", "Purchasing Reserved Instances at the optimal discount level", "Recommending optimal AWS compute resources based on actual usage patterns using ML", "Monitoring compute costs across all AWS accounts"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Compute Optimizer analyzes historical utilization metrics and uses ML to recommend optimal EC2 instance types, EBS volumes, ECS, and Lambda configurations, helping eliminate over-provisioning and reduce costs."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which cloud deployment model uses dedicated hardware for a single organization, hosted and managed by a third-party provider?","options":["Public cloud — multi-tenant shared AWS infrastructure", "On-premises private cloud — owned and operated by the organization", "Hosted private cloud — dedicated hardware managed by a third party", "Hybrid cloud — combining on-premises with public cloud"],"answer":2,"explain":"Hosted private cloud uses dedicated (single-tenant) infrastructure but the hardware is hosted and managed by a provider like AWS Outposts or managed hosting companies. Combines dedicated resources with managed operations."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is 'infrastructure as code' (IaC) and which AWS service implements it?","options":["Logging infrastructure configuration in a document for compliance", "Monitoring infrastructure health using automated scripts", "Writing application code that runs on AWS infrastructure", "Defining and provisioning infrastructure using code and templates — AWS CloudFormation"],"answer":3,"explain":"Infrastructure as Code (IaC) defines cloud infrastructure in version-controlled templates. AWS CloudFormation uses JSON/YAML templates to provision and manage AWS resources consistently, enabling repeatable deployments."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which pricing model allows customers to commit to a consistent compute usage amount in exchange for up to 72% discount vs On-Demand?","options":["On-Demand — pay for compute by the hour with no commitment", "Spot Instances — bid for unused EC2 capacity at up to 90% discount", "Reserved Instances or Savings Plans — commit to usage for 1 or 3 years for discount", "Dedicated Hosts — pay for a physical server dedicated to your use"],"answer":2,"explain":"Reserved Instances (1 or 3 year commitment) and Savings Plans offer up to 72% discount vs On-Demand in exchange for usage commitment. Best for steady-state workloads with predictable resource requirements."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A company is migrating and wants AWS to help identify which applications to move first. Which service provides migration assessment and planning?","options":["AWS Schema Conversion Tool for database migration", "AWS Migration Hub for tracking migrations across services", "AWS Application Discovery Service gathering on-premises data for migration planning", "AWS Database Migration Service for moving databases"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Application Discovery Service collects data about on-premises servers (performance, dependencies, configurations) to help plan migrations. It feeds into Migration Hub for tracking migration progress across DMS and SMS."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the concept of 'elasticity' vs 'scalability' in cloud computing?","options":["Scalability handles growing workloads by adding capacity; elasticity automatically adjusts capacity based on real-time demand", "They are identical concepts both meaning growing infrastructure", "Elasticity is vertical scaling; scalability is horizontal scaling", "Scalability applies to compute; elasticity applies only to storage"],"answer":0,"explain":"Scalability is the ability to handle increased load by adding capacity. Elasticity is the ability to automatically scale both up AND down in response to real-time demand, including releasing resources when no longer needed."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the AWS Partner Network (APN) and who uses it?","options":["A program for AWS customers to share reserved instance discounts", "A community forum for AWS developers to share solutions", "A network of AWS data centers connected via private fiber", "A global program for technology and consulting companies that build on and integrate with AWS"],"answer":3,"explain":"The AWS Partner Network (APN) includes technology partners (ISVs building on AWS) and consulting partners (system integrators, MSPs helping customers migrate/build). Partners have AWS-validated expertise and can resell AWS services."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which Well-Architected pillar focuses on the ability of a workload to perform its intended function correctly and consistently, and recover from failures?","options":["Operational Excellence — running and improving operations", "Security — protecting information and systems", "Reliability — recovering from failures and meeting demand", "Performance Efficiency — using resources efficiently"],"answer":2,"explain":"The Reliability pillar covers: automatic recovery from failure, testing recovery procedures, horizontal scaling, stopping guessing capacity, and managing change through automation. Key services: Route 53, RDS Multi-AZ, Auto Scaling."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is 'time to market' advantage in cloud computing?","options":["Cloud removes procurement delays, enabling businesses to launch products in days instead of months", "AWS guarantees faster application performance than on-premises", "AWS's global network delivers content faster to end users", "Cloud-native applications are inherently faster than traditional apps"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cloud dramatically reduces time to market: instead of 3-6 months to procure, rack, and configure servers, developers can launch new services in hours. This competitive advantage is especially critical for startups and digital businesses."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS service helps customers move petabyte-scale data to AWS when internet transfer would take too long?","options":["AWS DataSync for online data transfer via internet or Direct Connect", "Amazon Kinesis for streaming real-time data to AWS", "AWS Transfer Family for SFTP-based data transfer", "AWS Snowball Edge — physical device that ships to your data center for offline data transfer"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Snow family (Snowball, Snowmobile) provides physical devices for offline data transfer. Snowball Edge handles 80TB per device — faster and more cost-effective than internet transfer for large datasets."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What does the 'Sustainability' pillar (6th pillar) of the AWS Well-Architected Framework focus on?","options":["Long-term business sustainability and profitability in the cloud", "Ensuring workloads run sustainably without interruption", "Sustainable pricing through long-term Reserved Instance commitments", "Minimizing environmental impact by reducing energy consumption and carbon footprint"],"answer":3,"explain":"The Sustainability pillar (added 2021) focuses on minimizing environmental impact of cloud workloads: right-sizing resources, using graviton processors, optimizing code efficiency, and choosing regions powered by renewable energy."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the difference between AWS Local Zones and AWS Wavelength?","options":["They are identical services with different marketing names for different regions", "Local Zones bring AWS compute near large cities; Wavelength embeds AWS compute in 5G telecom networks for ultra-low latency", "Local Zones serve mobile users; Wavelength serves enterprise data centers", "Local Zones are for edge computing; Wavelength is for satellite connectivity"],"answer":1,"explain":"Local Zones extend AWS to major metro areas (LA, Chicago) for single-digit millisecond latency. Wavelength embeds AWS compute in 5G carrier networks for sub-10ms latency for mobile applications like gaming and AR/VR."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"Which AWS program lets startups get AWS credits, training, and support to build their businesses on AWS?","options":["AWS Free Tier for new accounts experimenting with services", "AWS Migration Acceleration Program for enterprise migrations", "AWS Activate providing credits, training, and support specifically for startups", "AWS Marketplace for purchasing startup software solutions"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Activate provides startups with AWS credits (up to $100,000+), technical training, business support, and access to startup-focused resources through accelerators, incubators, and VC partners."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is 'AWS Outposts' and when would a company use it?","options":["A service for moving applications out of AWS back to on-premises", "AWS-managed infrastructure installed in customer data centers for workloads that must stay on-premises", "A network peering service connecting on-premises to AWS", "A dedicated AWS region for government and regulated industries"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Outposts brings AWS hardware, services, and APIs to on-premises environments. Used for workloads requiring ultra-low latency to on-premises systems, data residency requirements, or existing on-premises investments."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"A financial company needs its AWS resources to only be accessible over a private dedicated network connection, not the public internet. Which service provides this?","options":["AWS Direct Connect — dedicated private fiber connection from data center to AWS", "VPN Gateway using encrypted tunnels over the internet", "VPC Peering connecting two VPCs privately", "AWS PrivateLink for private connectivity to AWS services"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Direct Connect provides a dedicated, private fiber connection from a customer's data center to AWS, bypassing the public internet. Ideal for consistent network performance, large data transfers, and compliance requirements."},
  {"cat":"cloud-concepts","q":"What is the purpose of the AWS Service Health Dashboard vs AWS Personal Health Dashboard?","options":["They are identical dashboards showing the same information", "Service Health Dashboard shows all AWS service status globally; Personal Health Dashboard shows issues affecting YOUR specific resources", "Service Health Dashboard is for enterprise customers; Personal Health Dashboard is for individual developers", "Personal Health Dashboard costs extra; Service Health Dashboard is free"],"answer":1,"explain":"Service Health Dashboard (status.aws.amazon.com) shows global AWS service status. Personal Health Dashboard (AWS Health) shows events specifically affecting your resources and provides proactive notifications for planned maintenance."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is an IAM policy and what are the two main types?","options":["A JSON document defining permissions; types are identity-based (attached to users/roles) and resource-based (attached to resources)", "A pricing policy for IAM user costs; types are pay-per-use and flat rate", "A security audit report; types are automated and manual", "A network access rule; types are allow and deny"],"answer":0,"explain":"IAM policies are JSON documents with Effect/Action/Resource/Condition. Identity-based policies attach to users, groups, roles. Resource-based policies attach to resources (S3 bucket policy, KMS key policy). Both use explicit allow/deny logic."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company has multiple AWS accounts and needs a centralized place to manage all security findings. Which service provides this unified security view?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty for threat detection across accounts", "AWS Security Hub aggregating findings from multiple security services across accounts", "AWS Config tracking compliance across all accounts", "IAM Access Analyzer analyzing resource permissions"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Security Hub provides a comprehensive view of security alerts and compliance status across AWS accounts, aggregating findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, and partner tools into a prioritized security dashboard."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What does AWS Macie do?","options":["Uses ML to discover, classify, and protect sensitive data (PII) stored in S3", "Monitors network traffic for malicious patterns", "Manages encryption keys for data at rest", "Scans EC2 instances for security vulnerabilities"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon Macie uses ML to automatically discover and protect sensitive data in S3, including PII (SSNs, credit cards, passport numbers), financial data, and healthcare information, helping with GDPR and HIPAA compliance."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service enables single sign-on for employees to access multiple AWS accounts and business applications with one set of credentials?","options":["AWS IAM Identity Center (SSO) for centralized single sign-on across accounts and applications", "AWS IAM for individual user authentication", "Amazon Cognito for customer-facing application authentication", "AWS Directory Service for Microsoft Active Directory integration"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS IAM Identity Center (formerly AWS SSO) provides centralized access management to multiple AWS accounts and cloud applications (Salesforce, Office 365). Employees sign in once using corporate credentials for all resources."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the difference between security groups and Network Access Control Lists (NACLs) in AWS?","options":["Security groups are for databases; NACLs are for web servers", "NACLs are stricter and override security group settings", "Security groups are stateful instance-level firewalls; NACLs are stateless subnet-level firewalls with explicit allow and deny rules", "Security groups require more configuration; NACLs are automatically configured"],"answer":2,"explain":"Security groups: stateful (track connections), instance-level, allow rules only, evaluate all rules. NACLs: stateless (must allow return traffic), subnet-level, allow AND deny rules, process rules in number order. Both apply to VPC traffic."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is AWS Shield Advanced and when would a company need it over Shield Standard?","options":["Shield Standard for small companies; Shield Advanced only for enterprises", "Shield Advanced adds DDoS cost protection, attack visibility, response team access, and advanced attack mitigation for sophisticated DDoS attacks", "Shield Advanced is required for all production AWS workloads", "Shield Advanced provides WAF rules; Shield Standard does not"],"answer":1,"explain":"Shield Advanced ($3,000/month) adds: 24/7 DDoS Response Team access, real-time attack visibility, cost protection (credits for DDoS-related scaling costs), advanced detection, and protection for EC2, ELB, CloudFront, Route 53, and Global Accelerator."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service helps prevent accidental public exposure of S3 buckets and other resources by analyzing resource policies?","options":["Amazon Macie scanning S3 for sensitive data exposure", "Amazon GuardDuty detecting unauthorized S3 access", "AWS Config checking S3 bucket public access settings", "IAM Access Analyzer identifying resources accessible from outside your account"],"answer":3,"explain":"IAM Access Analyzer examines resource policies (S3, IAM roles, KMS keys, Lambda, SQS) to identify resources shared with external entities, helping find unintended public access or cross-account sharing."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Under the shared responsibility model, who is responsible for patching the operating system on an EC2 instance?","options":["AWS — they manage all software running on their infrastructure", "Neither — EC2 instances automatically patch themselves", "Both AWS and customer share OS patching responsibility equally", "The customer — EC2 is IaaS so customers manage the OS and above"],"answer":3,"explain":"For EC2 (IaaS), customers own the OS and everything above: OS patches, application updates, runtime security. AWS manages the hypervisor and physical infrastructure. Contrast with RDS where AWS patches the database engine."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the difference between AWS KMS and AWS CloudHSM?","options":["KMS is for symmetric encryption; CloudHSM is for asymmetric encryption only", "KMS is a managed multi-tenant key service; CloudHSM provides dedicated FIPS 140-2 Level 3 hardware for customers requiring single-tenant HSMs", "CloudHSM is cheaper and better for most use cases than KMS", "They are identical services with different pricing models"],"answer":1,"explain":"KMS: managed, multi-tenant, FIPS 140-2 Level 2, easy integration with AWS services. CloudHSM: dedicated hardware, single-tenant, FIPS 140-2 Level 3, customer-controlled keys, needed for strict compliance requirements like government contracts."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which compliance framework is most relevant for companies storing healthcare data (PHI) in AWS?","options":["PCI DSS for payment card data protection", "HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) for protected health information", "SOC 2 for service organization security controls", "ISO 27001 for information security management systems"],"answer":1,"explain":"HIPAA governs protected health information (PHI). AWS signs a Business Associate Agreement (BAA) with healthcare customers and offers HIPAA-eligible services. Customers are responsible for HIPAA-compliant configurations."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is 'encryption in transit' and which protocol implements it for web traffic?","options":["Encrypting data as it travels across networks using TLS/SSL protocols", "Encrypting data on disk using AES-256 encryption", "Encrypting data before it leaves your application server", "Compressing data for faster network transmission"],"answer":0,"explain":"Encryption in transit (TLS/SSL) protects data moving between clients and servers, or between AWS services. AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) provides free SSL/TLS certificates for CloudFront, ALB, and API Gateway."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company needs to ensure no one in their organization can create resources in regions outside of us-east-1 and eu-west-1. What is the best approach?","options":["Create IAM policies denying all other regions for each user", "Set up CloudTrail alarms for API calls in unauthorized regions", "Configure AWS Config rules alerting on resources in other regions", "Use AWS Organizations SCPs to deny all actions in non-approved regions"],"answer":3,"explain":"SCPs in AWS Organizations can deny all actions in non-approved regions using Condition keys like aws:RequestedRegion. This creates an organization-wide guardrail that applies to all accounts, even administrators."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What AWS service continuously monitors and records AWS resource configurations, enabling compliance auditing and change tracking?","options":["AWS CloudTrail recording all API calls made in the account", "AWS Config recording resource configurations and changes over time", "Amazon CloudWatch monitoring metrics and system performance", "AWS Security Hub aggregating security compliance findings"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Config continuously records resource configurations and changes, evaluates against compliance rules, and maintains a configuration history. Enables questions like 'what did this security group look like 30 days ago?'"},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the purpose of an IAM permission boundary?","options":["A physical network boundary preventing unauthorized network access", "A feature preventing root account from performing certain actions", "A policy that limits maximum permissions an IAM entity can have, even if identity-based policies grant more", "A billing limit preventing spending above a certain threshold"],"answer":2,"explain":"Permission boundaries set the maximum permissions for an IAM entity. Even if an identity-based policy grants full admin access, if the boundary only allows EC2 access, the entity can only access EC2. Used to delegate permission management safely."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides managed Distributed Denial of Service (DDoS) protection and is automatically applied to all AWS customers at no charge?","options":["AWS WAF — web application firewall filtering layer 7 attacks", "AWS Network Firewall — managed VPC firewall service", "Amazon GuardDuty — detecting volumetric attack patterns", "AWS Shield Standard — automatic protection against network/transport layer DDoS at no cost"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Shield Standard is included free for all AWS customers, providing automatic protection against the most common, frequently occurring network and transport layer DDoS attacks that target AWS services."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to ensure that all EC2 instances in their AWS account always have encrypted EBS volumes. What is the most efficient way to enforce this?","options":["Manually encrypt each EBS volume when launching instances", "Create an IAM policy preventing creation of unencrypted volumes", "Use AWS Config rules to alert when unencrypted volumes are found", "Enable default EBS encryption in the account settings to encrypt all new volumes automatically"],"answer":3,"explain":"Account-level EBS encryption default ensures all newly created EBS volumes and snapshots are automatically encrypted using KMS, without requiring any action when launching instances. This is the simplest enforcement mechanism."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is Amazon Cognito and when is it used?","options":["An internal AWS authentication service for IAM users", "A user identity service for web and mobile applications providing authentication, authorization, and user management for customer-facing apps", "A corporate SSO service replacing Active Directory", "A multi-factor authentication service for AWS console access"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Cognito provides user pools (user directory with sign-up/sign-in) and identity pools (federated identity for AWS access) for customer-facing applications. Supports social logins (Google, Facebook) and SAML federation."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides a fully managed network firewall for filtering traffic entering and leaving VPCs?","options":["Security groups filtering EC2 instance traffic", "Network ACLs filtering subnet traffic", "AWS Network Firewall providing stateful deep packet inspection for VPCs", "AWS WAF filtering HTTP traffic at the application layer"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Network Firewall is a managed VPC firewall service providing stateful deep packet inspection, IPS (intrusion prevention), and URL filtering. Unlike security groups and NACLs, it supports Suricata-compatible rules for advanced threat detection."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the recommended best practice for the AWS root account?","options":["Use the root account for daily administrative tasks with MFA enabled", "Rotate root credentials every 90 days like other IAM users", "Only use the root account for initial setup, enable MFA, create IAM admin users for daily operations, and never share root credentials", "Give root account credentials to your most trusted administrator"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS best practices for root: enable MFA immediately, use only for tasks requiring root (initial billing setup, account closure), create IAM admin users for daily operations, never share credentials, never create programmatic access keys."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company must demonstrate to auditors that AWS meets specific compliance standards. What self-service AWS resource provides compliance documentation?","options":["AWS Security Hub showing compliance scores and findings", "AWS Config providing configuration compliance reports", "AWS Artifact providing on-demand AWS compliance reports, certifications, and agreements", "AWS Trusted Advisor showing security compliance best practices"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Artifact is a self-service portal providing: AWS compliance reports (SOC 1/2/3, PCI DSS, ISO), compliance agreements (HIPAA BAA, GDPR DPA), and security audit documentation for customer auditors."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What does the Principle of Defense in Depth mean for AWS security architecture?","options":["Using the most expensive security services for maximum protection", "Applying multiple layers of security controls so that if one layer fails, others provide protection", "Defending all AWS regions equally rather than focusing on one", "Using the deepest VPC subnets for sensitive workloads"],"answer":1,"explain":"Defense in depth layers security: WAF (application), Security Groups/NACLs (network), IAM (identity), KMS encryption (data), GuardDuty (detection), CloudTrail (audit). Multiple controls mean no single failure compromises everything."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the purpose of AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store?","options":["Managing EC2 instance parameters for Auto Scaling", "Managing CloudFormation template parameters for deployments", "Tracking system performance parameters across EC2 fleets", "Storing configuration data and secrets as key-value pairs for applications to retrieve securely"],"answer":3,"explain":"Parameter Store provides secure hierarchical storage for configuration data (database connection strings, feature flags) and secrets. Free tier available; integrates with IAM for access control. Secrets Manager adds automatic rotation for passwords."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service enables federated access to AWS using existing corporate identities from Microsoft Active Directory?","options":["AWS IAM creating native AWS user accounts", "AWS IAM Identity Center for multi-account SSO", "Amazon Cognito for customer application identity", "AWS Directory Service connecting AWS to Microsoft AD or running Managed AD in the cloud"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Directory Service provides options: AD Connector (proxy to on-premises AD), AWS Managed Microsoft AD (fully managed AD in AWS), and Simple AD. Enables employees to use existing Windows credentials for AWS console access."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A startup doesn't have dedicated security staff. Which AWS service provides automated security recommendations based on best practices for free?","options":["Amazon Inspector running vulnerability assessments", "AWS Trusted Advisor Basic providing core security checks for free", "AWS Security Hub aggregating security findings", "Amazon GuardDuty providing ML-based threat detection"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS Trusted Advisor Basic (free) provides core security checks: S3 bucket permissions, security group open ports, IAM usage, MFA on root, public EBS snapshots, and public RDS snapshots. A quick automated security review available to all."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What are the S3 storage classes and which is most appropriate for frequently accessed data requiring millisecond access?","options":["S3 Glacier — cheapest storage for frequently accessed data", "S3 Intelligent-Tiering — automatically moves data between tiers", "S3 Standard-IA — infrequent access tier for active data", "S3 Standard — high durability, availability, and performance for frequently accessed data"],"answer":3,"explain":"S3 Standard: 99.999999999% durability, 99.99% availability, millisecond access, no retrieval fee. Best for frequently accessed data like web assets, active datasets. More expensive than IA tiers but no retrieval charges."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"A company stores compliance data that is rarely accessed but must be retrievable within 12 hours at minimal cost. Which S3 storage class is best?","options":["S3 Standard — high performance but expensive for rarely accessed data", "S3 Standard-IA — lower storage cost with retrieval fee for infrequent access", "S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval — low-cost archival with retrieval times from minutes to 12 hours", "S3 Express One Zone — single-AZ for frequently accessed data"],"answer":2,"explain":"S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval (formerly Glacier) is for archival data: 90-day minimum storage, retrieval options from 1-5 minutes (Expedited), 3-5 hours (Standard), or 5-12 hours (Bulk). Far cheaper than S3 Standard for rarely accessed compliance data."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is S3 Intelligent-Tiering and when should it be used?","options":["Manually tiering data between S3 storage classes based on access patterns", "Intelligently distributing S3 objects across multiple regions for performance", "Automatically moving objects between frequent and infrequent access tiers based on actual access patterns — no retrieval fee", "A machine learning service that predicts future S3 storage needs"],"answer":2,"explain":"S3 Intelligent-Tiering monitors object access patterns and automatically moves objects between Frequent Access, Infrequent Access, and Archive tiers. No retrieval fees. Small monitoring charge per object. Best when access patterns are unknown."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is the difference between Amazon SQS and Amazon SNS?","options":["SQS is for mobile push notifications; SNS is for email notifications only", "SQS is a message queue for point-to-point messaging; SNS is a pub/sub service for broadcasting messages to multiple subscribers", "They are identical services with different use cases", "SQS stores messages permanently; SNS deletes messages after delivery"],"answer":1,"explain":"SQS: pull-based message queue, messages persist until processed, one consumer processes each message, decouples components. SNS: push-based pub/sub, one message fans out to many subscribers (email, SMS, SQS, Lambda, HTTP). Often used together: SNS→SQS fan-out."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon DynamoDB and what type of database is it?","options":["A fully managed NoSQL key-value and document database with single-digit millisecond performance at any scale", "A relational database supporting SQL queries and ACID transactions", "A time-series database optimized for metrics and monitoring data", "A graph database for relationship-heavy data like social networks"],"answer":0,"explain":"DynamoDB is a managed NoSQL database: serverless, auto-scaling, single-digit millisecond latency, 99.999% availability. Uses key-value or document model. No SQL joins — denormalize data. Unlimited scale with consistent performance."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is the difference between Amazon RDS Multi-AZ and Read Replicas?","options":["They are identical features with different names for different regions", "Read Replicas provide backup; Multi-AZ provides performance", "Multi-AZ provides high availability with automatic failover; Read Replicas improve read performance by serving queries from replica copies", "Multi-AZ is for MySQL; Read Replicas are for PostgreSQL only"],"answer":2,"explain":"Multi-AZ: synchronous replication to standby in another AZ, automatic failover for HA, standby cannot serve traffic. Read Replicas: asynchronous replication, can serve read traffic to scale reads, can be in different regions. Different purposes."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Aurora and how does it differ from standard RDS?","options":["Aurora is a NoSQL database; standard RDS is for relational workloads", "Aurora is more expensive but identical in performance to standard RDS", "Aurora is AWS's cloud-native relational database engine with 5x MySQL and 3x PostgreSQL performance, auto-scaling storage up to 128TB", "Aurora only works with PostgreSQL; standard RDS supports multiple engines"],"answer":2,"explain":"Aurora is AWS's re-engineered relational database: 6-way replication across 3 AZs, auto-scaling storage, up to 15 Read Replicas, serverless option (Aurora Serverless), and global databases spanning regions. MySQL and PostgreSQL compatible."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Lambda and what is the execution time limit?","options":["A serverless compute service running code in response to events with a maximum 15-minute execution timeout", "A managed container service running Docker containers with no time limit", "A virtual machine service for long-running background processes", "A workflow orchestration service for multi-step processes"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Lambda runs code without provisioning servers, scales automatically, charges per invocation (first 1M free). Maximum execution: 15 minutes per invocation. Best for event-driven workloads, APIs, and data processing under 15 minutes."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon ECS vs Amazon EKS?","options":["ECS is AWS's native container orchestration service; EKS is managed Kubernetes for teams already using or preferring Kubernetes", "ECS is for Windows containers; EKS is for Linux containers only", "EKS is simpler and cheaper; ECS is for enterprise workloads", "ECS uses Docker Compose; EKS uses Kubernetes YAML manifests"],"answer":0,"explain":"ECS: AWS-native container orchestration, simpler to learn, tightly integrated with AWS services, task definition JSON format. EKS: managed Kubernetes, use if you need Kubernetes ecosystem, portability, or already use Kubernetes on-premises."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Fargate and how does it differ from running containers on EC2?","options":["Fargate is for serverless functions; EC2 is for containerized applications", "EC2 provides more container orchestration features than Fargate", "Fargate is cheaper than EC2 for all container workloads", "Fargate is serverless containers — no EC2 instances to manage; compute scales automatically and you pay per container resource usage"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Fargate eliminates the need to provision and manage EC2 instances for containers. You define CPU/memory per container task and Fargate handles the infrastructure. Works with both ECS and EKS. Higher per-unit cost but less operational overhead."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon ElastiCache and what caching engines does it support?","options":["A CDN service caching web content at AWS edge locations", "A managed in-memory caching service supporting Redis and Memcached for sub-millisecond data access", "A database caching layer automatically added to all RDS instances", "A content delivery service caching S3 objects globally"],"answer":1,"explain":"ElastiCache provides managed Redis and Memcached clusters. Redis: data structures, persistence, pub/sub, read replicas, multi-AZ. Memcached: simple key-value, multi-threaded. Used to cache database query results, session data, reducing load on databases."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a petabyte-scale data warehouse for complex analytical queries across large datasets?","options":["Amazon RDS for relational database workloads", "Amazon Aurora for high-performance relational analytics", "Amazon DynamoDB for high-speed NoSQL analytical queries", "Amazon Redshift — managed petabyte-scale data warehouse using columnar storage"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon Redshift is a managed data warehouse using columnar storage and massively parallel processing (MPP). Ideal for BI, analytics, and complex SQL queries across petabytes of structured data from multiple sources."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Athena and what makes it cost-effective?","options":["A managed ETL service transforming data in S3", "A real-time streaming analytics service for Kinesis data", "A BI visualization tool for creating dashboards from AWS data", "Serverless SQL query service that analyzes data directly in S3 — you pay only per query scanned data, no infrastructure to manage"],"answer":3,"explain":"Athena is serverless SQL: query S3 data directly using standard SQL, no servers to provision. Pay $5/TB scanned (use columnar formats like Parquet to reduce costs). Ideal for ad-hoc analysis without a data warehouse."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Kinesis and what are its main components?","options":["A batch data processing service for transforming large datasets overnight", "A workflow orchestration service for data pipeline management", "A managed Kafka service for enterprise messaging at scale", "A real-time streaming data platform: Kinesis Data Streams (ingest), Firehose (deliver to destinations), and Analytics (process with SQL)"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon Kinesis handles real-time streaming: Data Streams ingests and stores streams for custom processing; Firehose loads streaming data to S3/Redshift/Elasticsearch; Data Analytics processes streams with SQL. Used for logs, IoT, clickstreams."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS CloudFormation and what problem does it solve?","options":["A monitoring service tracking the performance of cloud resources", "A cost management tool estimating cloud infrastructure expenses", "A deployment pipeline automating code testing and release", "Infrastructure as Code — define AWS resources in JSON/YAML templates to provision consistently and repeatably"],"answer":3,"explain":"CloudFormation creates, updates, and deletes AWS resource stacks from templates. Ensures consistent environments, enables version control of infrastructure, supports rollback on failure. Free (pay only for resources created)."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Elastic Beanstalk and what type of developers benefit most from it?","options":["A DNS service for automatically scaling web application domains", "A PaaS service handling deployment, scaling, load balancing, and monitoring so developers only upload code", "A container orchestration service for Docker applications", "A CI/CD pipeline for automated application testing and deployment"],"answer":1,"explain":"Elastic Beanstalk is PaaS: upload your code (Java, Python, Node.js, PHP, Ruby, .NET, Docker) and Beanstalk handles provisioning EC2, load balancing, auto-scaling, and monitoring. You retain control of the underlying resources."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon CloudWatch and what are its main capabilities?","options":["A network monitoring service tracking VPC traffic flows", "A monitoring and observability service providing metrics, logs, alarms, dashboards, and automated actions for AWS resources", "A security monitoring service detecting threats and suspicious activity", "A cost monitoring service tracking AWS spending patterns"],"answer":1,"explain":"CloudWatch provides: metrics (CPU, network, custom), logs (centralized log management), alarms (trigger Auto Scaling or SNS notifications), dashboards (visualization), Events/EventBridge (react to AWS events). Central observability platform."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Systems Manager and what operational problem does it solve?","options":["A suite of tools for viewing operational data, automating tasks, and managing EC2/on-premises servers at scale without SSH", "A service managing AWS support tickets and operational requests", "A configuration management service replacing traditional CM tools like Puppet", "A monitoring service providing system performance dashboards"],"answer":0,"explain":"Systems Manager provides: Session Manager (browser-based shell without SSH), Patch Manager (automated OS patching), Run Command (execute commands across fleets), Parameter Store (config management), and OpsCenter (operational incidents). No bastion hosts needed."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is the difference between an Application Load Balancer (ALB) and a Network Load Balancer (NLB)?","options":["ALB operates at layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS) enabling path-based routing; NLB operates at layer 4 (TCP/UDP) for ultra-high performance", "ALB is for HTTPS traffic; NLB is for HTTP traffic only", "NLB is newer and should replace ALB for all use cases", "ALB supports Auto Scaling; NLB requires manual scaling"],"answer":0,"explain":"ALB (Layer 7): path-based routing (/api → service A, /web → service B), host-based routing, sticky sessions, HTTP header rules. Best for microservices. NLB (Layer 4): millions of requests/second, static IP, TCP/UDP, ultra-low latency. Best for gaming, IoT."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What are EC2 placement groups and when would you use a 'Cluster' placement group?","options":["Cluster placement groups pack instances together in the same AZ for low-latency, high-throughput network performance for HPC", "Groups of EC2 instances in different regions for global distribution", "Groups of EC2 instances automatically distributed across AZs for high availability", "Spread placement groups placing instances on different hardware for fault tolerance"],"answer":0,"explain":"Cluster placement groups put instances physically close together in one AZ, enabling 10Gbps+ network performance and low latency. Ideal for HPC, big data, and applications requiring tight node communication. Trade-off: all in one AZ (single failure domain)."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Route 53 and what are its routing policies?","options":["A VPN service routing traffic between on-premises and AWS", "A managed DNS service with routing policies including simple, failover, geolocation, latency, weighted, and multivalue", "A network monitoring tool routing traffic away from unhealthy endpoints", "A Content Delivery Network routing users to the nearest edge location"],"answer":1,"explain":"Route 53 is AWS's managed DNS: resolves domain names to IP addresses. Routing policies: Simple (one record), Weighted (A/B testing), Latency (lowest latency), Failover (active/passive HA), Geolocation (route by user location), Geoproximity."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon VPC and what does it provide?","options":["A logically isolated virtual network in AWS where you control IP ranges, subnets, route tables, and gateways", "A VPN client for securely connecting to AWS from a laptop", "A peering service connecting multiple customer networks to AWS", "A dedicated network circuit from an on-premises data center to AWS"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon VPC is your private virtual network in AWS: define CIDR blocks, create public/private subnets, configure route tables, internet gateways, NAT gateways, and security groups. Your resources launch into your VPC, isolated from other customers."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is a NAT Gateway and why is it used?","options":["A managed service allowing instances in private subnets to initiate outbound internet connections while blocking inbound connections", "A gateway that translates private S3 URLs to public URLs for access", "A network peering gateway connecting two VPCs together", "A service translating IPv4 addresses to IPv6 for dual-stack support"],"answer":0,"explain":"NAT Gateway allows private subnet instances (no public IP) to access the internet for software updates etc., without being directly accessible from the internet. Highly available, managed by AWS. Deployed in public subnet, routed from private subnet."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Transit Gateway and what network problem does it solve?","options":["A hub-and-spoke network transit service connecting thousands of VPCs and on-premises networks through a central hub", "A CDN gateway routing content to the nearest edge location", "A gateway translating between on-premises protocols and AWS protocols", "A managed VPN service for encrypting traffic between VPCs"],"answer":0,"explain":"Transit Gateway solves the 'full-mesh VPC peering' problem. Instead of peering every VPC pair (n*(n-1)/2 connections), connect all VPCs and VPNs to one Transit Gateway hub. Simplifies network management for complex multi-VPC architectures."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Backup and what does it centralize?","options":["A service automating EC2 AMI creation for disaster recovery", "A database replication service for cross-region disaster recovery", "A centralized backup service managing backups across AWS services (EBS, RDS, DynamoDB, EFS, S3) with policies, retention, and compliance", "A snapshot management service only for EBS volumes"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS Backup provides a single console to manage backups across services: EBS volumes, RDS databases, DynamoDB tables, EFS file systems, S3, EC2 instances. Define backup plans with frequency, retention periods, and cross-region copy rules."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon EFS and how does it differ from Amazon EBS?","options":["EFS is block storage for databases; EBS is file storage for applications", "EFS is a shared managed file system accessible by multiple EC2 instances simultaneously; EBS is block storage attached to a single EC2 instance", "EBS is cheaper and should replace EFS for all use cases", "They are identical storage services with different pricing models"],"answer":1,"explain":"EBS: block storage, attached to ONE instance, use for OS/database (high IOPS). EFS: shared file system (NFS), mounted by MULTIPLE instances simultaneously, auto-scales. Use EFS for shared content, CMS, Docker containers needing shared storage."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service provides a fully managed GraphQL API that connects to DynamoDB, Lambda, and other data sources?","options":["Amazon API Gateway for RESTful API management", "AWS AppSync for managed GraphQL APIs with real-time subscriptions and offline data sync", "Amazon Cognito for API authentication and authorization", "AWS Amplify for full-stack mobile and web application development"],"answer":1,"explain":"AWS AppSync creates managed GraphQL APIs that resolve queries against multiple backends (DynamoDB, Lambda, HTTP, RDS). Supports real-time data subscriptions and offline client synchronization for mobile apps."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon SageMaker and what does it enable?","options":["A service for deploying pre-built AWS AI chatbots", "A data labeling service for creating ML training datasets", "A fully managed ML platform for building, training, and deploying machine learning models at scale", "An AutoML service that automatically selects the best algorithm"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon SageMaker is an end-to-end ML platform: data preparation (Data Wrangler), training (managed compute clusters), tuning (automatic hyperparameter optimization), hosting (real-time/batch inference endpoints), and MLOps (Pipelines, Model Monitor)."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Rekognition?","options":["A managed computer vision service for image and video analysis including object detection, face recognition, and content moderation", "A service for recognizing and translating multiple programming languages", "A natural language processing service for text analysis", "A speech recognition service converting audio to text"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon Rekognition analyzes images and videos: object/scene detection, face detection/recognition/comparison, text in images, activity detection in video, content moderation (nudity, violence), celebrity recognition. No ML expertise required."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Polly?","options":["A service converting text documents to PDF format", "A machine translation service converting between languages", "A text-to-speech service converting text into lifelike speech in multiple languages and voices", "A speech-to-text transcription service for audio files"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon Polly converts text to natural-sounding speech using deep learning. Supports 60+ voices, 30+ languages, SSML tags for pronunciation control, and neural TTS (NTTS) voices. Used for apps, e-learning, accessibility, and voice notifications."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"Which AWS service automatically transcribes audio and video files to text?","options":["Amazon Transcribe converting speech to text automatically", "Amazon Polly converting text to speech output", "Amazon Translate converting between written languages", "Amazon Comprehend extracting meaning from text documents"],"answer":0,"explain":"Amazon Transcribe uses automatic speech recognition (ASR) to convert audio to text. Features: speaker identification, custom vocabularies, medical transcription (HIPAA), streaming real-time transcription, and multiple language support."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Step Functions and what type of workloads is it designed for?","options":["A function-as-a-service compute platform for event-driven workloads", "A visual workflow service for orchestrating multi-step distributed applications and microservices with error handling", "A CI/CD pipeline service for coordinating deployment steps", "A data pipeline service for coordinating ETL transformation steps"],"answer":1,"explain":"Step Functions coordinates multiple AWS services (Lambda, ECS, DynamoDB, SNS) into serverless workflows using state machines. Handles retry logic, error handling, and parallel execution. Standard (audit trail) and Express (high volume) workflow types."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What are EC2 instance families and what does the 'C' family (C5, C6g) indicate?","options":["C means cheapest instance type for cost-optimized workloads", "C family indicates the fourth generation of EC2 instances", "C family instances are compute-optimized for CPU-intensive workloads like HPC, gaming servers, and ML inference", "C instances have the largest amounts of memory for data-intensive workloads"],"answer":2,"explain":"EC2 families: M (general purpose), C (compute-optimized, high CPU), R (memory-optimized), G/P (GPU), I (storage-optimized), T (burstable). C5/C6g: best price-to-performance for CPU-intensive workloads like scientific modeling, batch processing."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is VPC peering and what are its limitations?","options":["Connecting multiple AWS accounts under one organizational unit", "A networking connection between two VPCs allowing private routing — non-transitive (you can't route through a peered VPC to another)", "A VPN tunnel connecting on-premises networks to AWS VPCs", "A service aggregating multiple VPCs into a single network namespace"],"answer":1,"explain":"VPC Peering connects two VPCs (same/different account/region) for private routing. Key limitation: non-transitive — if A↔B and B↔C, A cannot reach C through B. CIDR ranges cannot overlap. For many VPCs, use Transit Gateway instead."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon CloudFront and how does it improve application performance?","options":["A CDN distributing content from 400+ global edge locations, caching content close to users to reduce latency and origin load", "A database caching layer for RDS that reduces query latency", "A DNS service routing users to the lowest-latency AWS region", "A load balancer distributing traffic across multiple EC2 instances"],"answer":0,"explain":"CloudFront caches static content (images, CSS, JS) and dynamic content at 400+ edge locations worldwide. Cache hits are served from the nearest edge, reducing origin load and dramatically reducing latency for global users."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon API Gateway used for?","options":["A physical network gateway connecting corporate networks to AWS", "A database query gateway routing SQL to appropriate database backends", "A fully managed service for creating, publishing, securing, and monitoring REST, HTTP, and WebSocket APIs at any scale", "A load balancer specifically designed for API traffic"],"answer":2,"explain":"API Gateway creates managed APIs: REST APIs (feature-rich), HTTP APIs (cheaper, faster), WebSocket APIs (real-time). Handles traffic management, authorization (Cognito, Lambda), throttling, caching, and monitoring. Integrates with Lambda for serverless backends."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS Glue and what type of workload is it designed for?","options":["A service bonding multiple S3 buckets into a unified storage namespace", "A schema migration service for moving database schemas between engines", "A data compression service for reducing S3 storage costs", "A serverless ETL (Extract, Transform, Load) service for preparing and loading data for analytics"],"answer":3,"explain":"AWS Glue is serverless ETL: Data Catalog (metadata store), crawlers (discover schemas), ETL jobs (Spark/Python transforms data), and DataBrew (visual data preparation). Prepares and transforms data from S3/databases for Athena/Redshift analytics."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What are the three types of AWS Free Tier offers?","options":["Always Free (never expire), 12-Month Free (for new accounts), and Short-Term Trials (30-90 days for specific services)", "Monthly, Annual, and Multi-Year free tiers based on commitment length", "Basic, Standard, and Premium free tiers based on usage level", "Development, Testing, and Production free tiers by environment type"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Free Tier has 3 types: Always Free (Lambda 1M requests/mo, DynamoDB 25GB forever), 12-Month Free (EC2 750hrs t2.micro, S3 5GB, RDS 750hrs for new accounts), and Trials (SageMaker 2 months, Redshift 2 months)."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is the difference between Standard Reserved Instances and Convertible Reserved Instances?","options":["Standard RIs offer higher discounts (up to 72%) but cannot change attributes; Convertible RIs allow changing instance family/OS/tenancy with slightly lower discounts (up to 66%)", "Standard RIs are monthly commitments; Convertible RIs are annual commitments", "Convertible RIs are more expensive with no additional flexibility benefits", "Standard RIs can be sold on the marketplace; Convertible RIs cannot"],"answer":0,"explain":"Standard RIs: highest discount (72%), can sell unused RIs on Marketplace, cannot change instance type/OS/tenancy. Convertible RIs: slightly lower discount (66%), can exchange for different RI attributes during the term. Both offer 1 or 3-year terms."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is the AWS Pricing Calculator used for?","options":["Estimating the cost of AWS architectures before building them by modeling services and configurations", "Calculating your actual current AWS bill from usage data", "Comparing AWS prices to other cloud providers automatically", "Recommending cost optimizations for existing AWS deployments"],"answer":0,"explain":"The AWS Pricing Calculator (calculator.aws) lets you model AWS architectures before deployment: add services, configure them, and get monthly/annual cost estimates. Ideal for budgeting, TCO analysis, and comparing architectural options."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is the data transfer pricing model for AWS? Which direction is free?","options":["All data transfer is free within AWS; charges only apply for storage", "Data transfer is charged equally in both directions based on volume", "Inbound data transfer to AWS is free; outbound data transfer to the internet is charged per GB", "Only cross-region data transfer is charged; same-region transfer is always free"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS data transfer pricing: INBOUND to AWS = free. OUTBOUND to internet = charged (first 100GB/month free, then per-GB rates). Data transfer BETWEEN AZs in same region = small charge. Using CloudFront reduces outbound data transfer costs."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is AWS Cost Anomaly Detection?","options":["A manual process for reviewing monthly AWS bills for irregularities", "A budget alarm that triggers when spending exceeds a set threshold", "A security service detecting unauthorized resource creation causing unexpected costs", "An ML-powered service that automatically monitors spending and alerts you when unusual cost patterns are detected"],"answer":3,"explain":"Cost Anomaly Detection uses ML to analyze your historical spending patterns and automatically detect unusual increases — sudden cost spikes, gradual increases, or unexpected new services. Sends alerts via SNS/email before they become large bills."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is the difference between AWS Budgets alerts and CloudWatch billing alarms?","options":["AWS Budgets monitors actual and forecasted costs with granular filtering; CloudWatch billing alarms only trigger when actual charges exceed a threshold", "They are identical services with different names in different AWS console locations", "CloudWatch billing alarms are more sophisticated than AWS Budgets", "AWS Budgets is for enterprises; CloudWatch billing alarms are for individual developers"],"answer":0,"explain":"AWS Budgets: track actual and FORECASTED costs, filter by service/tag/account, set usage budgets, 62-day alert history. CloudWatch billing alarms: simple threshold on actual spend. Budgets is more comprehensive for proactive cost management."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is Spot Instance pricing and what type of workload is it best suited for?","options":["Discounted pricing for Reserved Instances paid upfront", "A pricing model for Savings Plans flexible compute commitment", "Pricing for dedicated hosts with no interruption risk", "Deeply discounted (up to 90%) EC2 instances using AWS spare capacity — can be interrupted with 2-minute notice, best for fault-tolerant workloads"],"answer":3,"explain":"Spot Instances use AWS spare capacity at up to 90% discount. AWS can reclaim them with 2-minute notice. Best for: batch processing, big data, CI/CD, ML training, rendering — workloads that can checkpoint and restart on interruption."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is the purpose of AWS Cost Explorer?","options":["Exploring new AWS services before purchasing them", "Exploring cost-saving opportunities by comparing Reserved Instance pricing", "Visualizing, analyzing, and forecasting AWS costs and usage over time with filtering and grouping capabilities", "A tool for calculating costs before deploying new AWS architectures"],"answer":2,"explain":"Cost Explorer provides graphs of past 13 months of AWS spending, forecasts next 12 months, and lets you filter by service, account, region, tag. Identifies top cost drivers, shows RI/Savings Plan utilization, and recommends purchases."},
  {"cat":"billing-pricing","q":"What is Compute Savings Plans and how does it differ from EC2 Instance Savings Plans?","options":["Compute Savings Plans apply only to EC2; EC2 Instance Savings Plans apply to all compute", "Compute Savings Plans apply to EC2, Fargate, and Lambda across any region/family/OS; EC2 Instance Savings Plans offer higher discounts but are restricted to specific EC2 family and region", "They have identical discounts but different service coverage", "EC2 Instance Savings Plans are purchased annually; Compute Savings Plans monthly"],"answer":1,"explain":"Compute Savings Plans (up to 66% off): most flexible — applies to EC2 regardless of family/size/region, plus Fargate and Lambda. EC2 Instance Savings Plans (up to 72% off): higher discount but locked to a specific EC2 instance family and region."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the purpose of VPC Flow Logs and what information do they capture?","options":["Application-level logs showing HTTP requests to EC2 instances", "CloudTrail logs filtered for VPC-specific API calls", "Security group rule change logs for compliance auditing", "Network traffic metadata (source/destination IP, port, protocol, bytes, accept/reject) flowing through VPC network interfaces"],"answer":3,"explain":"VPC Flow Logs capture metadata about IP traffic to/from network interfaces: source/destination IPs, ports, protocol, packet count, bytes, and whether traffic was ACCEPTED or REJECTED by security groups/NACLs. Used for network monitoring and security analysis."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service helps detect and protect sensitive data like credit card numbers and SSNs stored in S3?","options":["Amazon GuardDuty for detecting unauthorized S3 access attempts", "Amazon Inspector scanning S3 objects for security vulnerabilities", "AWS Config checking S3 bucket encryption settings", "Amazon Macie using ML to discover and classify sensitive data in S3"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon Macie uses ML to automatically discover sensitive data (PII, financial data, credentials, intellectual property) in S3 buckets, classify it, and alert on policy violations. Critical for GDPR, CCPA, and PCI compliance."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the purpose of using IAM groups?","options":["Grouping AWS accounts under a management account for billing", "Attaching permissions to collections of IAM users to manage access at scale rather than individually", "Grouping EC2 instances for applying security groups collectively", "Creating permission boundaries for a set of related IAM roles"],"answer":1,"explain":"IAM groups let you attach policies to multiple users at once. Instead of managing permissions for 50 developers individually, create a 'Developers' group with appropriate policies. Users inherit all group permissions. A user can belong to multiple groups."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"A company wants to give an EC2 instance permission to write to an S3 bucket securely without storing credentials on the instance. What is the best approach?","options":["Store IAM user access keys in a .env file on the EC2 instance", "Attach an IAM role to the EC2 instance with S3 write permissions — temporary credentials are automatically provided", "Create an IAM user and store credentials in Parameter Store on the instance", "Use the root account credentials in the application configuration"],"answer":1,"explain":"IAM roles attached to EC2 instances provide temporary credentials via instance metadata (automatically rotated). The application calls AWS SDK/CLI and credentials are provided automatically. No keys to manage, rotate, or accidentally expose."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is AWS Certificate Manager (ACM) and what does it provide?","options":["A managed service providing free SSL/TLS certificates for AWS services like CloudFront, ALB, and API Gateway with automatic renewal", "A compliance certification tracking service for regulatory requirements", "A tool for generating compliance audit certificates for SOC and PCI", "A service managing code signing certificates for Lambda deployments"],"answer":0,"explain":"ACM provides free public SSL/TLS certificates for AWS services. Automatic renewal eliminates certificate expiration risks. Integrates with CloudFront, Application Load Balancer, API Gateway, and Elastic Beanstalk. No private key management needed."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the purpose of AWS GuardDuty's threat intelligence integration?","options":["Using customer-provided lists to block known bad IP addresses at the network level", "Providing intelligence reports about emerging AWS-specific threats to security teams", "Importing threat feeds to populate WAF rules automatically", "GuardDuty correlates API calls, network flows, and DNS logs with known malicious IPs, domains, and behavioral patterns to identify threats"],"answer":3,"explain":"GuardDuty uses AWS threat intelligence (known bad IPs, Tor exit nodes, malware command-and-control domains) plus ML anomaly detection to identify compromised instances, credential abuse, reconnaissance, and crypto mining — no agents needed."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the principle of 'immutable infrastructure' and how does it improve security?","options":["Infrastructure that cannot be modified or scaled after initial deployment", "Replacing servers rather than patching them in-place — ensures known good state, eliminates configuration drift and persistent access", "Using hardware security modules that cannot be tampered with physically", "Locking IAM permissions so they cannot be modified after creation"],"answer":1,"explain":"Immutable infrastructure: instead of patching running servers (which accumulate drift), create new AMI with updates and replace instances. Eliminates configuration drift, ensures consistent deployments, and removes persistent access from attackers who may have compromised old instances."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides automated compliance checking against standards like CIS AWS Foundations Benchmark?","options":["AWS Security Hub running automated compliance checks against CIS, PCI DSS, and other standards", "AWS Trusted Advisor checking basic security best practices", "AWS Config rules evaluating specific resource configurations", "Amazon Inspector scanning for known CVE vulnerabilities"],"answer":0,"explain":"Security Hub runs automated, continuous compliance checks against standards: CIS AWS Foundations Benchmark, PCI DSS, AWS Foundational Security Best Practices. Provides pass/fail findings with remediation guidance across your accounts."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is data sovereignty and how does AWS help customers maintain it?","options":["AWS owning all data stored in its infrastructure for service improvement", "Encrypting data so AWS cannot access customer information", "The principle that data is subject to the laws of the country where it resides — customers choose AWS regions and data never leaves without explicit action", "Sharing data only with sovereign (government) customers in regulated regions"],"answer":2,"explain":"Data sovereignty: customer data is subject to laws of the country where it physically resides. AWS lets customers choose which region stores their data, and data does not replicate cross-region without customer action. Enables GDPR, data residency compliance."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is a bastion host (jump box) and what modern AWS service replaces the need for one?","options":["A highly available EC2 instance used as a primary application server", "An internet-accessible instance used as a gateway to access private instances — AWS Systems Manager Session Manager eliminates the need for one", "A dedicated hardware server for cryptographic key operations", "A monitoring server collecting logs from all EC2 instances in a VPC"],"answer":1,"explain":"Bastion hosts are EC2 instances in public subnets used to SSH/RDP into private instances. Security risk: exposed public IP, port 22/3389 open. AWS Systems Manager Session Manager provides browser-based shell access to private instances via IAM — no bastion, no open ports."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"Which AWS service provides real-time visibility into your AWS account's adherence to security best practices and compliance standards?","options":["Amazon CloudWatch monitoring operational metrics and performance", "Amazon GuardDuty detecting active threats in your account", "AWS CloudTrail logging API calls for audit and investigation", "AWS Security Hub providing continuous security and compliance posture management"],"answer":3,"explain":"Security Hub provides a centralized security and compliance dashboard: aggregates findings from multiple services, runs compliance checks (CIS, PCI, NIST), provides Security Score, and shows findings prioritized by severity with remediation guidance."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is the purpose of S3 Block Public Access settings?","options":["Preventing EC2 instances from accessing S3 buckets over the public internet", "Blocking public S3 traffic for cost savings by forcing private transfer", "Account-level and bucket-level settings that prevent S3 objects from being made publicly accessible, overriding any permissive bucket or object policies", "A firewall preventing DDOS attacks on public S3 static websites"],"answer":2,"explain":"S3 Block Public Access (enabled by default for new buckets) prevents public access regardless of bucket policies or ACLs. Can be set account-wide to prevent any S3 bucket in the account from being made public — critical default security control."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is AWS Firewall Manager and when is it used?","options":["A service managing EC2 security group rules across all instances", "A centralized service for managing WAF rules, Shield Advanced, and security groups across all accounts in an AWS Organization", "A network firewall for filtering traffic entering and leaving VPCs", "A tool for automating security group cleanup and removing unused rules"],"answer":1,"explain":"Firewall Manager centrally configures and manages WAF rules, Shield Advanced protections, VPC security groups, Network Firewall, and Route 53 DNS Firewall across all accounts in an AWS Organization, ensuring consistent security posture."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is a 'confused deputy' attack and how does the aws:SourceAccount condition key prevent it?","options":["When a service acting on your behalf is tricked into acting for another account — aws:SourceAccount ensures the service only acts when called from your account", "A social engineering attack targeting AWS account managers", "A man-in-the-middle attack on AWS API calls between services", "An attack where a confused attacker gets IAM credentials from the wrong account"],"answer":0,"explain":"Confused deputy: malicious actor tricks a service (like CloudTrail, Config) with permissions into acting on their behalf. Using aws:SourceAccount and aws:SourceArn condition keys in resource policies ensures the service only acts when called from your specific account."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What is AWS WAF's rate-based rule and how does it protect applications?","options":["A WAF rule that counts requests from a single IP within a 5-minute window and blocks IPs exceeding the threshold — protects against brute force and web scraping", "A rule that charges different WAF prices based on traffic volume", "A rule that rates the severity of WAF findings from low to critical", "A traffic shaping rule that slows down requests rather than blocking them"],"answer":0,"explain":"WAF rate-based rules block IPs that exceed a request threshold in a 5-minute window. Protects against credential stuffing, brute force login attempts, web scraping, and layer 7 DDoS. The IP is automatically unblocked when the rate drops below the threshold."},
  {"cat":"security-compliance","q":"What does 'zero trust security' mean in an AWS context?","options":["Never trusting, always verifying — authenticate and authorize every request regardless of network location, eliminating implicit trust based on network perimeter", "Trusting no vendors and only using open-source AWS-compatible tools", "Setting all IAM permissions to deny everything by default", "Using zero servers by adopting a fully serverless architecture"],"answer":0,"explain":"Zero trust: never trust implicitly based on network location (VPN/intranet doesn't automatically grant access). Always verify identity (IAM), validate device (GuardDuty), minimize access (least privilege), assume breach. IAM Identity Center + IAM policies implement this."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What are EC2 Auto Scaling policies and what is the difference between target tracking and step scaling?","options":["Auto Scaling policies are for Reserved Instances only; On-Demand uses manual scaling", "Target tracking scales horizontally; step scaling scales vertically", "They are identical policies with different names for different EC2 families", "Target tracking maintains a metric at a target value (e.g., 50% CPU); step scaling adds/removes capacity in steps based on alarm breach size"],"answer":3,"explain":"Target tracking: simplest — set CPU to 50%, Auto Scaling adjusts automatically. Step scaling: define scale-out steps (CPU 70%: add 2, CPU 85%: add 4). Scheduled scaling: known traffic patterns. Predictive scaling: ML-based proactive scaling."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon EBS and what are the main volume types?","options":["Elastic Bandwidth Service — a network optimization service for EC2", "A distributed file system for sharing storage across multiple EC2 instances", "Elastic Block Store — persistent block storage for EC2: gp3/gp2 (general purpose SSD), io2 (provisioned IOPS), st1 (throughput HDD), sc1 (cold HDD)", "A backup service taking automatic snapshots of EC2 instance storage"],"answer":2,"explain":"EBS volume types: gp3 (general purpose SSD, default, up to 16,000 IOPS), io2 Block Express (highest performance, databases), st1 (throughput HDD, big data/logs), sc1 (cold HDD, cheapest, infrequent access). Only one EC2 can attach most EBS volumes at a time."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS CodePipeline and how does it relate to CI/CD?","options":["A project management tool for tracking software development progress", "A fully managed continuous delivery service that automates build, test, and release pipelines for fast software updates", "A code repository service for storing and versioning source code", "A deployment service for automatically scaling application infrastructure"],"answer":1,"explain":"CodePipeline automates the software release process: Source (CodeCommit/GitHub) → Build (CodeBuild) → Test → Deploy (CodeDeploy/Elastic Beanstalk/ECS). Enables frequent, reliable releases. Part of the AWS Developer Tools suite alongside CodeCommit, CodeBuild, CodeDeploy."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Comprehend and what type of analysis does it perform?","options":["A service for understanding and analyzing AWS cost and billing data", "A natural language processing service that extracts insights from text — sentiment, entities, key phrases, language, and topics", "A log analysis service for understanding CloudWatch log patterns", "A business intelligence tool for analyzing operational metrics"],"answer":1,"explain":"Amazon Comprehend is NLP-as-a-service: analyzes unstructured text to extract sentiment (positive/negative/neutral), named entities (people, places, organizations), key phrases, language detection, and topic modeling. No ML expertise required."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Lex and what applications is it used to build?","options":["A text editor service for building cloud-native applications", "A translation service for converting text between languages in applications", "A natural language search service for querying S3 data lakes", "A service for building conversational interfaces (chatbots and voice assistants) using the same technology as Amazon Alexa"],"answer":3,"explain":"Amazon Lex uses automatic speech recognition (ASR) and natural language understanding (NLU) to build conversational chatbots and voice assistants. Powers customer service bots, ordering systems, and FAQ bots. Uses the same technology as Alexa."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is Amazon Translate and when would a global company use it?","options":["A service translating AWS CloudFormation templates between JSON and YAML", "A neural machine translation service for translating text between languages in real-time for multilingual applications", "A protocol translation service for connecting legacy systems to AWS APIs", "A currency translation service for converting between payment currencies"],"answer":2,"explain":"Amazon Translate provides real-time and batch neural machine translation between 75+ languages. Used for multilingual customer support, content localization, social media monitoring, and real-time communication translation in global applications."},
  {"cat":"cloud-technology","q":"What is AWS X-Ray used for in application development?","options":["Monitoring AWS billing and detecting unusual cost patterns", "Scanning code for security vulnerabilities before deployment", "Distributed tracing service for debugging and analyzing distributed applications and microservices — shows request flow across services", "Visualizing VPC network topology and traffic patterns"],"answer":2,"explain":"AWS X-Ray traces requests through distributed applications: shows service maps, identifies bottlenecks and errors, measures latency across services (Lambda, EC2, API Gateway, DynamoDB). Essential for debugging microservices and understanding performance issues."}
];